<TEXT>
a laboratory accused of mishandling blood 
samples taken from exxon valdez skipper joseph hazelwood issued a 
statement thursday attempting to explain what happened 
lawyers for hazelwood said the statement left too many questions 
unanswered they continued to assert that the blood testing for 
alcohol was botched and followed by a coverup which denied 
hazelwood his right to a fair trial earlier this year in alaska in 
the nations worst oil spill 
compuchem the north carolina parent company of chemwest a 
sacramento laboratory that received hazelwoods blood acknowledged 
that three glass tubes containing his blood were mislabeled by a 
lab technician 
that took place when the tubes were received four days after the 
exxon valdez struck a reef in alaskas prince william sound in 
march 1989 spilling 11 million gallons of crude in the nations 
worst oil spill 
the labs finding that hazelwoods blood had a 06 alcohol 
content was the cornerstone of his prosecution on criminal charges 
though a jury acquitted him of being intoxicated the image of 
the drunken skipper hung over the proceeding 
hazelwoods lawyers contend discrepancies in descriptions of the 
tubes in which the blood for hazelwoods blood was shipped to 
california for the alcohol test suggest the lab results could be 
for the wrong person 
coast guard technician scott m conner who drew hazelwoods 
blood 10 hours after the exxon valdez grounding testified in the 
alaska trial and before the national transportation safety board 
that he placed hazelwoods blood in three 15milliliter tubes two 
had gray stoppers and one had a red stopper he said 
chemwests first inventory sheet showed it had received 
hazelwoods blood in three 10 milliliter red stoppered tubes on 
march 28 1989 
the colored stoppers are used to differentiate the contents of 
the blood tubes 
graytopped blood tubes contain a chemical added to prevent 
blood alcohol from fermenting and thus reaching a reaching a higher 
level red tubes are used for drug testing and are considered 
unreliable for alcohol because they are untreated 
on thursday compuchems statement said adhesive evidence tape 
obscured a technicians view of the blood tube stoppers 
while the color of the vial stoppers was initially 
misidentified because the stoppers were covered by adhesive 
evidence tape this was subsequently discovered and properly 
corrected said the lab statement 
but on may 1 1989 the inventory sheet appears to have been 
changed the number 3 is crossed out and a 1 is substituted for the 
number of red tubes a handwritten line adds that two 
graystoppered tubes were received the size of the tubes is still 
logged at 10 milliliters 
hazelwoods lawyers were outrage at the labs explanation about 
the tape 
blood was taken from all of the crew members that day said 
attorney thomas russo if there were security seals on his tubes 
they should have been on all of the tubes how come they got the 
others right 
identifications on samples of all other crew members conformed 
with conners testimony he said 
why did she say the stoppers were red if she couldnt see 
them did she just make that up russo asked referring to 
technician karen s metcalf who signed the documents 
he noted that even after the corrections the sizes of the 
tubes were still wrong 
compuchem vice president paul brunswick whose name appeared on 
the statement was unavailable for comment late thursday a call to 
his north carolina office after business hours was unanswered 
there was nothing that occurred during the chemwest handling 
andor testing of the hazelwood samples that invalidates the chain 
of custody or the laboratory testing results said the statement 
hazelwoods lawyers complained that the blood documents were 
withheld from them until four months after his trial was over 
though they had repeatedly asked to see everything relevant to the 
blood tests 
the lab said the documentation went to authorized officials 
and to the national transportation safety board when the trial 
began in february 
there are strict legal limitations regarding the release of 
such information to others it added these precautions are 
necessary to protect individual rights and confidentiality 
hazelwood lawyer michael chalos had a different interpretation 
of the withholding of documents 
what they did was deprive capt hazelwood of his rights 
chalos said 
he alleged that the ntsb the coast guard and the state of 
alaska also may have had the documents and withheld them 
chemwest handled the receipt testing and reporting of the 
hazelwood samples correctly and totally in compliance with 
established forensic drug testing procedures said the statement 
issued for compuchem by a new york public relations firm 
the ntsb is scheduled to issue its final report on the exxon 
valdez disaster next tuesday russo and chalos have said the newly 
discovered documents should be taken into account if the board is 
planning to say whether hazelwood was intoxicated 
a coast guard administrative law judge suspended hazelwoods 
captains license for nine months in a plea bargain announced 
wednesday the coast guard dropped two charges including one that 
he was intoxicated and hazelwood pleaded no contest to two other 
charges including one that he drank alcohol within four hours of 
sailing 
</TEXT>
