<TEXT>
a man accused of hijacking two city buses from 
depots early wednesday told detectives he wanted to work for the 
transit authority police sources said 
the first bus was grabbed in manhattan and driven 25 miles 
across the borough of queens but it wasnt until the second bus 
was spotted zooming out of the queens depot at 445 am that the 
double theft was discovered 
a sharpeyed transit manager later spotted the second bus coming 
off the triborough bridge in manhattan recognized that it was in 
the wrong borough and started a chase that resulted in the 
suspects capture 
darius mccollum 25 of queens was charged with grand larceny 
after his arrest at grand central station at about 6 am said 
police spokesman officer scott block 
police sources who spoke on the condition of anonymity said 
mccollum told detectives he stole the buses because the transit 
authority wouldnt hire him 
investigators were checking transit authority records to see 
whether mccollum had applied for a job or taken a test to become a 
bus driver 
detectives were also trying to verify mccollums boasts that he 
had commandeered a subway train about 10 years ago as a teenager 
twentyfive city buses have been stolen in the last 12 months 
according to transit authority statistics unfortunately its 
going up we are seeing a trend said transit authority 
spokeswoman caren gardner 
mccollum is considered a suspect in other bus thefts said 
transit police spokesman al oleary 
what someone wants to do with a transit authority bus i cant 
begin to tell you ms gardner said the bright blue and silver 
buses which are 40 feet long by nine feet wide are kind of 
recognizable and not usually taken for joyrides 
the manager who spotted the bus at 530 am waved down a police 
car and officers gave chase 
the driver jumped from the moving bus in front of grand central 
and the bus rolled into a parked new york telephone truck causing 
no damage to either vehicle ms gardner said 
mccollum was arrested inside grand central 
</TEXT>
