<TEXT>
an american animal rights activist posted a 
petition in st peters square calling on pope john paul ii to 
declare that animals have immortal souls and sought a meeting with 
the pontiff 
but security guards quickly took down the statement on wednesday 
and shooed away the activist john stockwell of berkeley calif 
and several of his followers and a private audience was not 
granted 
stockwell a 55yearold geologist and school teacher compared 
his initiative to that of martin luther the protestant reformation 
leader who posted his historic 95 theses on the door of a castle 
church in wittenberg germany in 1517 
what were seeking is the beginning of a humane and ecological 
reformation stockwell said 
he said he had hoped for a meeting with the pope but was not 
granted one stockwell and several followers attended the popes 
general audience wednesday morning but they were given seats far 
from the pontiff 
later the group gathered in st peters square and stockwell 
taped a sheet of paper containing his 10 theses to the base of 
a marble column near the entrance to the basilica 
after photographers snapped pictures vatican guards moved in 
removed the petition and asked the group to leave the area 
stockwell applauded a recent statement by the pope that gods 
breath also touched animals but said he wanted john paul to go 
further 
his petition declares that all animal species have immortal 
souls it also calls for a ban on hunting fishing medical and 
scientific research on animals and all forms of abuse and cruelty 
in an address to scientists in 1982 the pope said it is 
certain that animals are at the service of man and can hence be the 
object of experimentation nevertheless they must be treated as 
creatures of god which are destined to serve mans good but not to 
be abused by him 
