<TEXT>
an israeli arab poet has pleaded innocent to 
charges he incited antiisraeli violence with his writings 
at the opening day of his trial wednesday shafik habib a 
49yearold accountant from nazareth acknowledged he had written 
the book of poetry on which the charges are based 
but he denied that his political poetry constituted 
incitement 
habib was jailed and then held under house arrest for several 
weeks in june after police charged that his poems could incite 
violence the military censor banned further publication of the 
poems 
the action was taken under an antiterror statute that dates 
back to the days of british control 
the arrest ignited protests by arab legislators and arab 
writers unions they said they feared the move could signal a 
government crackdown on writers and other artists 
the court in this northern port city was told wednesday that 
habibs poetry urged violence against jews and supported the 
31month palestinian uprising against israeli occupation of the 
west bank and gaza strip 
the charges say habibs poetry encourages readers to fight back 
with stones molotov cocktails and explosives 
judge rahamin tsemah agreed to delay further proceedings until 
sept 30 after habib complained that the translation of his book 
from arabic to hebrew was not precise 
</TEXT>
