<TEXT>
its an argument among statisticians 
economists and intelligence analysts matching eyeglazing formulas 
and rival numbers that measure the magnitude of soviet military 
spending with a very big price tag behind the debate 
central intelligence agency estimates of the soviet economy its 
performance and the share moscow was spending on the military have 
been a factor in us defense planning and budgeting for the past 
40 years 
now the cia numbers are being challenged 
a democratic senator says soviet economic strength has been 
vastly overestimated for years prompting an american military 
buildup that helped run the united states deep into debt 
a top economic adviser to president bush said he thinks the 
soviet gross national product last year was substantially lower 
than the cia estimated 
soviet economists free to speak after decades of cold war 
silence on such topics say their nations economic performance was 
far weaker than the cia judged it to be 
and an analyst at the defense intelligence agency said at a 
senate hearing that the cia clearly understates the share of 
the soviet economy devoted to military expenditures 
william t lee a longtime cia critic said that agencys 
methods are flawed and likely to be as unreliable and 
misleading in the future as in the past 
but the cia insists that essentially it has been correct 
i think we have done a very good job on a very complex 
issue george kolt cia director of soviet analysis said last 
week at the senate foreign relations committee hearing but that 
does not mean that our numbers are totally accurate they are 
estimates that are most likely on the high side 
the current cia estimate is that the soviet gross national 
product amounts to 51 percent of that in the united states which 
had a 1989 gnp of 42 trillion 
michael j boskin chairman of bushs council of economic 
advisers said he thinks the soviet gnp is about onethird that of 
the united states 
at a conference sponsored by the american enterprise institute 
in april soviet economists and statisticians offered even lower 
estimates one soviet official victor belkin said his nations 
gnp could be as low as 14 percent of that in the united states and 
no higher than 28 percent 
sen daniel patrick moynihan dny says the cia estimates of 
soviet economic strength and military capabilities in the mid1970s 
led to the massive defense buildup that began when jimmy carter was 
president and accelerated under ronald reagan 
moynihan said the senate committee should look further into the 
consequences of government statistics about the soviet union 
would we have spent as much on our military during the 1980s 
if we had believed that the soviet defense burden simply was not 
sustainable he asked i think not and if i am correct then 
this issue has been a momentous one for the state of the american 
economy 
moynihan said that just as the united states was launching its 
military buildup soviet economists were predicting disaster for 
their economy 
the cias kolt said that while the agency considers its estimate 
of the defense burden generally accurate the threat to the united 
states isnt represented by that number anyhow but by soviet 
weapons and forces 
and those are easier to count than economic statistics 
defense spending accounts for about 6 percent of the us gross 
national product kolt said the cia had estimated that 15 to 17 
percent of the soviet gross national product has been going into 
military spending although that has declined since last year 
defense secretary dick cheney said he thinks it is running at 
about 25 percent but doubts it will stay that high 
soviet military spending will decline as a matter of policy 
and because it cant be sustained he said i think they 
are in a depression 
nevertheless cheney said the soviet military is maintaining 
and modernizing its strategic forces thats what makes them a 
superpower and they wont give that up he said 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
walter r mears vice president and columnist 
for the associated press has reported on washington and national 
