<TEXT>
a trade spat between two big southeast asia 
rice producers is helping dampen export prospects for us rice 
farmers 
but an agriculture department report says tight supplies are 
likely to keep us prices firm in the coming year at least 
above sagging world prices 
over the last year world prices have weakened in response to 
increased competition in world markets especially between thailand 
and vietnam and a drop in world trade the report said wednesday 
the export competition is expected to heat up further in the 
199091 rice marketing year that begins aug 1 
currently the report said vietnam has cut into thailands 
markets by selling at prices substantially below those offered 
by thai exporters thailand is the worlds largest rice exporter 
recently thailand announced an export subsidy scheme in an 
effort to increase exports but the response has been weak the 
report said 
meanwhile thailands market share dropped from 40 percent in 
1989 to 31 percent forecast for 1990 
it is expected that thailand will aggressively compete with 
vietnam to regain market share in 1991 the report said 
the us global market share is forecast to fall to about 18 
percent in 1991 from 20 percent the past two years usda analysts 
said tight supplies and relatively high prices may hinder us 
competitiveness in some foreign markets 
analysts said us rice production this year may be about 158 
million hundredweight up only 23 percent from the 1989 harvest 
based on acreage and yieldtrend projections the first official 
rice estimate will be included in usdas aug 9 crop report 
however conditions to date indicate that yields may not match 
last years record the report said rain and wet field 
conditions this spring delayed planting in the mississippi delta 
which could reduce yield potential 
currently based on the latest projections the us rice 
stockpile going into the new marketing year on aug 1 is expected 
to be 238 million hundredweight down from 267 million a year ago 
and 314 million two years ago 
if production and total use turns out as projected the rice 
stockpile a year from now could be about unchanged from the current 
level the report said 
