a report to congress says the agriculture 
department should review more closely a proposal to remove import 
inspections on canadian meat and poultry entering the united states 
the proposal was announced by usda last month with july 30 set 
as a deadline for public comments if adopted the experimental 
plan would be in effect for one year 
officials of the departments food safety and inspection service 
said canadian products would still be thoroughly inspected at 
slaughter and processing plants under a system that is nearly 
identical to the us system and standards 
but reinspection of random samples at border points would be 
eliminated under the proposal a reciprocal nod would be given us 
products entering canada 
the general accounting office the investigative arm of 
congress said in a recent report that the departments inspection 
agency has not documented how it arrived at the determination that 
canadas system is virtually identical to that of the united states 
further the gao said unexplained 1989 rejection rates for 
canadian meat inspected randomly at border points are cause for 
concern 
according to the report usda inspectors rejected about 3 
percent of the selected products compared with 1 percent in 1988 
without an adequate explanation the rates could be 
interpreted as indicating a decline during 1989 in the 
effectiveness of the canadian inspection system the report said 
