<TEXT>
granting temporary amnesty to tax evaders in 
order to reduce the budget deficit could make honest taxpayers feel 
cheated and lose more money than it gains the bush administration 
says 
a federal tax amnesty program is a gamble with our tax 
systems most important asset the general willingness of 
taxpayers to obey the law said michael j graetz deputy 
assistant secretary of the treasury for tax policy 
the vast majority of taxpayers who already comply with tax 
laws might feel cheated if they see that those who knowingly broke 
the rules are allowed to escape punishment graetz told the house 
government operations subcommittee on consumer affairs wednesday 
tax amnesty is a popular proposal in congress as lawmakers look 
for ways to reduce the budget deficit without raising taxes or 
cutting spending too deeply 
the internal revenue service estimates that cheating on income 
taxes will cost 87 billion in lost revenue this year in addition 
the longterm backlog of taxes that corporations and individuals 
admit owing but have not paid will total in the 80 billion range 
this year 
several bills would give wayward taxpayers six months in which 
to settle their accounts with the irs in return the agency would 
waive penalties and under some bills forgive interest and 
forgo civil or criminal prosecution 
the bills also promise considerably toughened enforcement after 
amnesty ends and include an expanded auditing and collection force 
at the irs 
as we battle headlong to reduce our uncontrollable budget 
deficit debating over whether to cut essential programs or impose 
unwanted taxes on our citizens we should take advantage of the 
benefits that a tax amnesty program yields sen alan dixon 
dill sponsor of one amnesty bill told the subcommittee 
sen kent conrad dnd noted that the 1991 budget prepared by 
the senate budget committee endorses the amnesty program he has 
proposed which congressional authorities estimate would bring in 
an extra 637 billion over five years 
its both fiscally irresponsible and insulting to the vast 
majority of honest taxpayers in this country if we fail to tap this 
revenue from those who havent complied conrad told the 
subcommittee 
graetz the treasury official called conrads estimate an 
exaggeration we do not believe a federal amnesty program would 
raise large additional revenues and there is a risk that such a 
program in fact might lose revenue he said 
irs commissioner fred t goldberg jr also said a general 
federal tax amnesty would be illadvised and counterproductive 
even so he said the irs is studying results from the 31 states 
that have offered amnesty and considering proposals that might be 
designed to provide an opportunity for a fresh start to those 
individuals who are not reached by our current tax administration 
efforts 
state amnesties have produced 16 billion in gross revenues 
but graetz and goldberg said there is no reason to expect a federal 
amnesty would bring in large amounts 
federal enforcement efforts already are far more effective than 
those used by any state graetz said in addition a considerable 
part of the increased state revenues probably were attributable to 
the tougher enforcement that accompanied amnesty he said 
goldberg said any workable amnesty would have to be highly 
targeted and part of a massive program to update irs computers and 
tighten enforcement there should be no forgiveness of interest or 
amnesty in taxshelter cases he said 
under the best of circumstances goldberg said there are 
serious doubts that the irs could implement any amnesty program 
during the next several years 
