<TEXT>
an alliance of government and private highway 
safety advocates wants to give police the power to take away a 
drunken drivers license on any road in the country 
claiming successes in 29 states where automatic revocation laws 
are in effect the heads of the national transportation safety 
board and the national highway traffic safety administration called 
wednesday for a campaign to pass similar laws in the rest of the 
nation 
the aim is to give police in every state the power to suspend 
the license of a driver who refuses or fails a roadside breath test 
for alcohol consumption 
the action is taken administratively without a court decision 
a nonjudicial hearing may be held if the driver appeals the laws 
have passed all court tests in states where they have been applied 
officials said 
in most states the illegal level of alcohol in the blood is 
010 percent but five states california colorado oregon maine 
and utah have set the level at a more stringent 008 percent 
the surgeon general has recommended that all states adopt the 
tougher law and eventually go as low as 004 percent for adults and 
000 for any driver under 21 
more than 16 million drivers are arrested each year on drunken 
driving charges and about half of all the 45000 traffic 
fatalities each year are alcoholrelated according to the traffic 
safety agency 
we hope the coalition will stay active until we get the 
administrative revocation law in all 50 states said ntsb 
chairman james l kolstad whose independent board has called for 
such laws in its investigations of drunken driving accidents 
kolstad and traffic safety agency administrator jerry r curry 
met with representatives of safety advocacy groups the insurance 
industry police organizations and others to plan a campaign for 
passage of laws in the remaining 21 states 
the fact that in the morning a driver has a license and if he 
or she is foolish and drinks at lunchtime and then fails a breath 
test the license is lost on the spot would be a strong incentive 
against drinking and driving kolstad said 
curry said he had followed drunken drivers through the process 
of losing their licenses being taken to a hospital for verifying 
tests being processed at a police station and then having to be 
driven home by someone else 
its an absolutely debilitating experience you think youre a 
criminal you are a criminal this is a violent crime he said 
without such laws we have to go through the court system and 
if were not able to get a trial date that particular drunks 
license might not be pulled for months curry said 
the administrator said the laws may be tough to get passed in 
legislatures where it has become a states rights issue its 
going to be a hard push he said 
opponents of the laws include some police agencies who are 
concerned about the extra hearings required when drivers appeal 
the revocations from trail lawyers who defend arrested drivers 
and from some state motor vehicle officials concerned about the 
administrative costs 
the federal government offers incentives of up to several 
million dollars to states which pass automatic revocation laws 
