spending adopted by the senate armed services committee a total 
of 289 billion that slashes 18 billion from his original request 
for the 1991 fiscal year 
in a session with vice president dan quayle defense secretary 
dick cheney and national security adviser brent scowcroft bush 
also urged lawmakers to approve continued production of the b2 
bomber elements of the antimissile strategic defense initiative 
and other major weapon systems 
but with the house armed services committee beginning to craft a 
defense bill today to the houseapproved figure of 283 billion 
and democrats certain to push for deep cuts gop lawmakers pressed 
the administration to indicate what level of spending is acceptable 
theres no bottom line for sdi no suggestion for b2 said 
dickinson he said he is willing to operate on his instincts but 
would prefer that the administration state what is totally 
unacceptable 
republicans conceded that the administration is faced with a 
difficult task because congressional and white house negotiators 
have yet to reach agreement on how to cut 50 billion from the 
deficit in fiscal 1991 which begins oct 1 
the whole thing is lost in the mist of the budget summit 
said rep joseph mcdade of pennsylvania ranking republican on the 
house appropriations defense subcommittee 
in the white house session mcdade said he proposed that cheney 
and the ranking members of the congressional armed services and 
defense appropriations subcommittees work to reach agreement on a 
military budget total 
but that proposal received little support from lawmakers who 
want to avoid preempting the budget summit 
conservative democrats and republicans are also pushing the 
president to lobby harder for various weapons warning that without 
a phone call from bush or an invitation to the white house the 
program may be severely cut or killed 
everybody indicated that the president has to engage 
himself mcdade said he understands it 
sen sam nunn dga chairman of the senate armed services 
committee said after the white house meeting that it will take 
strenuous efforts by bush cheney and scowcroft to save the b2 
stealth bomber 
the house armed services committee is poised to follow its 
chairman rep les aspin dwis and end the program at the 15 
planes currently in production 
support for the radarevading aircraft is eroding in the 
100member senate where opponents say privately they have 40 solid 
votes to cancel the weapon 
the dire predictions come as aspins committee is weighing a 
reduction in bushs proposed budget of 47 billion for sdi to 29 
billion said congressional sources who requested anonymity 
the senate armed services committee in approving its version of 
the bill cut nearly 1 billion from the presidents request 
several house armed services panels were beginning work on the 
defense bill today with the seapower and strategic and critical 
materials subcommittee facing the toughest task cutting 3 
billion from bushs request of 163 billion for the navy 
the panels chairman rep charles bennett dfla said it will 
likely approve funds for one trident nuclear missile submarine and 
one seawolf attack submarine 
the senate armed services committee in its bill approved 12 
billion for the navys 18th trident sub but deferred the 
administrations request to buy two seawolfs for 23 billion 
