<TEXT>
major legislation to curb job discrimination 
is headed for house floor action with sponsors brushing off bush 
administration warnings that it would usher in the use of minority 
hiring quotas 
we did not bring forth a bill that will lead to quotas or any 
danger of quotas rep don edwards dcalif said wednesday 
before the house judiciary committee approved the bill 2412 
house speaker thomas foley dwash said last week that the 
measure which closely matches a bill already passed by the senate 
would not come up for house floor action until after lawmakers 
return from their august recess 
civil rights forces however are urging him to reconsider and 
bring the bill to the floor before the break 
five supreme court decisions last year would be effectively 
overturned by the bill the top legislative priority of the civil 
rights movement 
provisions range from a ban on racial harassment in the 
workplace to punitive damages for discrimination victims in extreme 
cases 
at the core of the debate is a provision designed to overcome a 
supreme court ruling that favors employers in certain 
discrimination lawsuits 
until last year companies could win if they proved the 
employment practices leading to the disparity were required by 
business necessity the new ruling made it easier for 
employers placing on those filing suit the burden of proving the 
practices in question were not business necessities 
the combination of damages plus the bills definition of 
business necessity would trigger an upsurge in discrimination 
suits critics say 
this should really be called the plaintiffs lawyers full 
employment act of 1990 rep f james sensenbrenner jr rwis 
told the judiciary committee 
under the bill business owners would feel compelled to turn to 
racial and ethnic hiring quotas as a way of protecting themselves 
in advance from such lawsuits the administration contends 
president bush has said repeatedly that he would like to sign a 
bill to combat job bias but not one that would lead to quotas 
the judiciary committees majority democrats easily beat back 
republicansponsored amendments designed to limit damages courts 
could award discrimination victims and tighten the rules governing 
fairhiring lawsuits 
rep barney frank dmass conceded there are horror stories 
about overenforcement of similar laws but he said such 
instances were rare and that those intent on discriminating often 
would find the means to get away with it 
the advantage is overwhelmingly with the sophisticated 
bigot he said 
rep henry j hyde rill said the problem was that the 
phrasing of the bill does more than merely negate last years 
supreme court decision and actually represents gains for civil 
rights forces 
i would concede the employer groups do not want a level 
playing field they want one that assists them hyde said but 
i also learned that the civil rights groups do not want a level 
playing field 
the house education and labor committee whose chairman rep 
augustus hawkins dcalif is a chief sponsor along with edwards 
already has approved the legislation 
two minor amendments were adopted by the judiciary committee 
before it approved the measure one would clarify the definition of 
business necessity 
the second would encourage the use of dispute resolution 
procedures outside the court system to resolve discrimination cases 
rep craig t james rfla a veteran attorney expressed 
skepticism he said urging nonjudicial settlements was a 
beautiful sentiment but that the amendment was a waste of 
paper because it would never be used 
</TEXT>
