in a legislative race epitomizing 
the conflict between young reformers and the old guard in the new 
political climate a lawyer with no political experience is taking 
on the communist party boss 
ganbold the 29yearold candidate of the fledgling party of 
national progress favors rapid privatization and bold political 
change 
he says he volunteered to challenge 61yearold gombojavyn 
ochirbat arguably the most powerful man in mongolia in ulan 
bators 12th district race for the great peoples hural 
it is the first time the hurals 430 seats are being contested 
by noncommunist parties and the communists say that shows how far 
mongolia has strayed from its authoritarian past in the seven 
months since they agreed to reform under pressure of prodemocracy 
street rallies 
ganbold and other opposition candidates want more change and 
are finding considerable support among voters in the capital 
in last sundays primary ochirbat received the most votes but 
nearly half went to opposition candidates including ganbold 
the other opposition parties are now backing ganbold the only 
remaining opposition candidate in the district and have given the 
race top priority in this sundays second decisive round of 
balloting 
the communist party in mongolia is already going down not 
