<TEXT>
a satellite that will illuminate 
earths invisible magnetic field in shades of red white and blue 
orbited the world today after a flawless ride into space on an 
unmanned rocket 
the 143foot atlas rocket roared into a clear sky wednesday from 
cape canaveral air force station and the satellite separated as 
planned after several delays 
its always a good feeling to see a launch vehicle leave the 
ground nasa manager sid saucier said so far everything is 
going great 
it was the fourth attempt in six days by nasa and rocket builder 
general dynamics to launch the atlas the first commercial version 
of the rocket ever flown the postponements were caused by a helium 
leak bad weather and a corroded power transfer switch in the 
rocket 
the weather was perfect as the atlas boosted the 189 million 
combined release and radiation effects satellite to an orbit 217 
miles by 22236 miles high to study radiation in space 
the 2ton satellite a joint program of nasa and the defense 
department holds 24 chemicalfilled canisters that will be ejected 
starting this fall ultraviolet rays from the sun will ionize the 
released barium lithium and other chemicals creating large 
glowing clouds that will spread along earths magnetic field lines 
the bariumladen clouds will resemble the aurora borealis or 
the northern lights the display will be visible to the naked eye 
enabling scientists to measure electric fields in space and see how 
they interact with normally invisible charged particles 
the first releases will be made over american samoa in the south 
pacific in september four months later people in north america 
will get their first glimpse of the clouds additional canisters 
will be released next summer over the caribbean providing a view 
from florida and the southern portions of alabama and georgia 
wednesdays launch was the first of a commercial atlas and the 
eighth commercial rocket launch by an american company nasa used 
earlier versions of the atlas to launch planetary probes and other 
midsize payloads 
