<TEXT>
researchers have found a defect in the 
bodys scaffolding that may cause a genetic disease that makes 
people unusually tall and lanky and might have affected abraham 
lincoln 
the disease called marfan syndrome can also include severe 
heart problems that may cause basketball players to die suddenly on 
the court dr reed pyeritz of the johns hopkins school of medicine 
in baltimore said wednesday 
pyeritz and his colleagues identified the defect in a protein 
called fibrillin a component of the elastic fibers in skin blood 
vessels and ligaments 
theres something wrong with the scaffolding and glue that 
holds us together pyeritz said at the jackson laboratory in bar 
harbor where some of the nations leading researchers have 
gathered for an annual genetics course 
lynn sakai of the oregon health sciences university who 
collaborates with pyeritz has identified the gene for fibrillin 
and is now conducting studies to determine its function 
she said in a telephone interview that she and pyeritz soon will 
be able to confirm whether a defect in the fibrillin gene and the 
consequent defect in fibrillin itself are the cause of marfan 
syndrome 
meanwhile a research group in finland has obtained preliminary 
evidence through an entirely different approach that the genetic 
defect for marfan syndrome is on chromosome 15 one of the 23 pairs 
of human chromosomes 
if the fibrillin gene is also on chromosome 15 that will be 
further evidence that the gene is indeed the cause of the disorder 
sakai said 
if fibrillin is lnked that would be quite a breakthrough 
she said 
doctors have speculated that lincoln had marfan syndrome not 
only because he was tall and lanky but also because toward the end 
of this life he had an illness that could have been congestive 
heart disease pyeritz said 
that is one of the consequences of a defect that causes the 
aorta the principal output vessel from the heart to expand and 
tear 
the aorta problem is also what causes the oncourt death of 
basketball players and can cause sudden death in others with marfan 
syndrome pyeritz said 
the discovery of the gene for marfan syndrome would enable 
doctors to begin devising new treatments but it would not 
guarantee any change in the near future for marfan victims pyeritz 
said 
people with the disorder can currently be helped by surgery to 
replace part of the aorta with a dacron tube pyeritz said 
other aspects of the disease can be difficult to treat however 
many patients have a dislocation of the lenses in their eyes and 
some are blind others have curvature of the spine chest 
deformities and loose joints 
the work by pyeritz and sakai and their colleagues identifying 
fibrillin comes after researchers have tried for years to determine 
what defect could cause such a wide range of symptoms 
the elastic fibers containing fibrillin are found in eye 
ligaments bones blood vessels and other affected tissues pyeritz 
said 
