<TEXT>
former exxon valdez skipper joseph 
hazelwood could be back in command of a ship in nine months under a 
penalty imposed by the coast guard for the nations worst oil spill 
hazelwood in an interview said he was satisfied that the coast 
guard dismissed misconduct and negligence charges against him and 
decided to let him to resume his career 
at a coast guard hearing wednesday administrative law judge 
harry gardner suspended hazelwoods captains license for nine 
months and put him on probation for three more months 
misconduct and negligence charges were dismissed after hazelwood 
agreed to enter nocontest pleas on two other counts that he 
violated coast guard policy by drinking liquor less than four hours 
before taking command of the tanker and that he improperly left 
the vessels bridge while it was headed for jagged bligh reef 
but hazelwood said after the hearing he was angered by newly 
disclosed papers about crucial bloodalcohol tests that had implied 
he was drunk when the tanker spilled nearly 11 million gallons of 
crude last year 
hazelwoods attorneys said the blood analyzed may not have been 
his 
its what we said all along and nobody would listen to us 
hazelwood said the possible skulduggery that goes along with it 
is enough to make anybody angry 
if it werent for our discovery of this it would have been 
buried forever and a lot of people with political agendas would 
have been very happy 
hazelwoods attorneys contended that evidence may have been 
covered up a charge the coast guard and national transportation 
safety board denied 
the 987foot tanker was en route from the alaskan port of valdez 
to long beach on march 24 1989 when it struck the reef in prince 
william sound 
