editors note the following is based partly on a pool report 
from journalists in monrovia associated press correspondent 
michael goldsmith was a member of the pool 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
rival rebel groups are closing in on 
the city from two directions in heavy fighting for control of the 
capital 
as the battles raged wednesday the airfield that was monrovias 
last link to the outside world also came under attack 
fighters of rebel leader charles taylor resumed their offensive 
in the eastern part of the city followers of a rival rebel 
commander prince johnson fought off government soldiers who tried 
to retake bushrod island in the north 
with gunfire echoing all around acting information minister 
paul allen wie told reporters that president samuel doe had no 
plans to step down despite the advancing armies 
the president thinks it is worth dying for his country wie 
said at a news conference at the ducor palace hotel he distributed 
a news release quoting doe as saying a sudden resignation would 
lead to greater anarchy and ethnic tragedy in liberia 
i cannot heed the advice to quit the leadership of liberia 
because it would introduce a dangerous precedent of outrageous 
rebellion and instability into the west african region doe said 
early wednesday prodoe troops attacked two bridges that link 
the city center with rebelheld bushrod island but they were 
repulsed by heavy fire 
one squad of government soldiers was seen crawling across one of 
the bridges but was pinned down under the heaviest gunfire yet 
heard in the battle for the city 
some of the soldiers lay motionless as though dead or injured 
others ran back to the safety of the government positions 
shells were also seen exploding on the other bridge hitting a 
government jeep which was trying to lead an attack from that side 
the wreckage of the jeep sat in the middle of the bridge 
government troops firing from the city center shelled rebel 
positions on the far side of the bridges some rounds falling close 
to the citys main oil storage depot which was in rebel hands 
state department spokesman richard boucher said it appeared 
johnsons men controlled the island which includes the port 
johnson is believed to have split with taylor sometime in the 
past three months and some diplomats say his army is now stronger 
than taylors national patriotic front 
a few miles away to the east rebels waded across a swamp and 
attacked spriggspayne airfield the last way out of the city that 
was not in rebel hands it was unclear whether fighters of johnson 
or taylor launched the airfield attack 
further east in paynesville taylors men resumed their 
offensive diplomats reported heavy fighting in that area where 
the rebels had been blocked several weeks by government soldiers 
diplomats said taylors forces surrounded and effectively 
neutralized government troops who were barricaded inside the radio 
and television stations east of the city the rebels did not attack 
them in order to spare the facilities the diplomats said 
the government which the rebels accuse of corruption and human 
rights abuses repeated its allegation the united states was 
actively aiding the insurgents 
the united states has denied the accusation and boucher said 
its offer to provide safe passage out of the country for doe stood 
doe met tuesday with us ambassador peter de vos but did not ask 
for help in leaving the country boucher said at a washington 
briefing 
the liberian people are disappointed by the united states 
wie told the reporters 
doe expelled the chief of the us military mission to liberia 
col david staley on friday after accusing him of actively 
supporting the rebels 
on tuesday the government accused the united states of 
launching an attack on does presidential mansion from a submarine 
a charge immediately denied by washington 
people who said they witnessed the attack said it came from a 
rebel gunboat offshore the fortified mansion returned the fire and 
later announced that five civilians were killed on a nearby main 
road 
monrovians continued their desperate search for food and water 
in a city where all shops were closed and where utilities have been 
shut down for more than a month 
as many as 5000 people were jammed into a usowned fuel 
storage depot near the embassy in the exclusive mamba point 
district seeking haven from attacks by soldiers who were going on 
looting sprees and attacking civilians 
most government soldiers are members of does krahn tribe since 
the insurgency began in december they have attacked civilian 
members of the gio and mano tribes which provide the main support 
for taylor 
sixteen ambassadors met with the acting foreign minister 
wednesday to complain about being harassed by troops at checkpoints 
throughout the city 
