<TEXT>
a juror today was removed from deliberations 
for a huge moneylaundering trial after reports that a member of 
the jury apparently telephoned members of a colombian drug ring for 
more information 
us district judge william terrell hodges held a closed hearing 
today on whether to declare a mistrial few details were available 
because of a gag order in effect for lawyers and their clients for 
the duration of the trial 
but court clerk john gay said the original panel of 12 is down 
to eleven alternate jurors were dismissed after testimony ended 
and deliberations can continue with eleven jurors when both sides 
agree there was no immediate indication if any action was taken 
against the dismissed juror 
gay said transcripts of todays hearing and two meetings 
wednesday will be made public when they are transcribed but that 
could take several days 
attorneys learned wednesday that one of the 12 jurors undertook 
some independent investigation including making telephone calls to 
purported medellin drug cartel members in colombia and then shared 
information with another juror according to a report in todays 
tampa tribune 
five employees of the luxembourgbased bank of credit and 
commerce international and a colombian airplane broker are accused 
of conspiring with an undercover us customs service agent to 
launder 14 million in proceeds from the sale of cocaine in six 
us cities 
the first public indication of trouble in the sixmonth trial 
surfaced wednesday morning when jurors were sent home shortly after 
reporting to begin their fourth day of deliberations 
the judge met privately with prosecutors and defense attorneys 
twice wednesday to discuss the situation the lawyers and court 
personnel refused to discuss the problem or divulge what occurred 
during the private meetings 
the newspaper reported that the juror who telephoned cartel 
members got the phone numbers from an address book that was 
introduced into evidence at the trial authorities took the book 
from the briefcase of one of the defendants colombian rudolf 
armbrecht when he was arrested in a miami motel in october 1988 
us attorney robert w genzman and larry curtin spokesman for 
the tampa fbi office had no comment 
jurors were specifically instructed by hodges to decide the case 
only on evidence and testimony presented during the trial and were 
told to avoid and ignore any outside information they have not 
been sequestered and have been allowed to return home throughout 
the trial 
the defendants in the case are ian howard and sibte hassan of 
bccis paris branch amjad awan and akbar a bilgrami of bccis 
miami branch syed aftab hussain who worked in panama and the 
colombian aircraft broker armbrecht 
