<TEXT>
a federal judge fined general electric co 
10 million today for overcharging the government about 8 million 
for an army battlefied computer system 
us district judge lowell reed jr called the fine adequate 
fair and in the best interest of the public 
federal prosecutors said ge convicted in february on 286 
criminal counts agreed to pay 10 million for those charges 
under the deal ge waived its right to appeal 
reed also sentenced gerald a leo 52 a former employee of 
management amp technical services co a ge subsidiary to 10 months 
in prison and fined him 15000 leo was convicted on four counts 
of mail fraud and one count of trying to deceive federal 
investigators in the case 
he never did anything his wife mary yelled as reed handed 
down the sentence today 
leo will remain free while his case is appealed 
james badolato another former employee of the same subsidiary 
faced sentencing later today badolato 43 was convicted of 
misleading auditors and submitting false documents 
assistant us attorney nicholas harbist said the fine was the 
second largest criminal fine imposed in any defense contracting 
case the largest he said was 17 million against northrop in a 
case involving defective parts for a cruise missile 
prosecutors said the company also agreed to pay 83 million to 
settle related civil suits and 117 million to settle unrelated 
civil suits 
ge the nations secondlargest defense contractor was 
convicted in february of four counts of mail fraud and 282 counts 
of making false claims 
the government charged that the ge subsidiary did not tell the 
government in 1983 that it had shaved its costs by hiring 
substantially lessexpensive subcontractors to help build the 
battlefield computer system the defense contract was worth 250 
million 
