<TEXT>
the senate has approved a 20 million research 
and prevention program to keep zebra mussels from invading farm 
irrigation systems 
the striped mollusk which is not native to north america has 
caused problems at water and power plants throughout the great 
lakes they attach to water intake pipes and clog them 
an amendment authorizing the 20 million over five years was 
added to the 1990 farm bill by sen daniel p moynihan dny 
unlike other infestations this one is irreversible 
moynihan said in a statement thursday the zebra mussel is here 
to stay within 20 years time it will have spread through the 
entire surface water system of north america 
the amendment which the senate passed late wednesday directs 
the department of agriculture and the us army corps of engineers 
to develop a program of research prevention and design criteria 
for irrigation systems with an emphasis on keeping the mussels out 
on wednesday scientists expressed surprise that the tiny 
mollusks are spreading through the erie canal system from buffalo 
ny and now threaten rochester ny and the finger lakes region 
frankly i did not think their advance would be this fast 
said cameron lange a biologist studying the mussels movement for 
a consortium of power companies 
i thought we might find a few at lockport during our late july 
sample but i did not think theyd reach rochester by now 
rochester is about 60 miles east of lockport ny 
in may the senate committee on environment and public works 
authorized 375 million in grants and research funding for control 
of the mussel the provision is part of the pending water resources 
development act of 1990 
