<TEXT>
the easing of federal controls on lowlevel 
atomic wastes poses public health concerns the environmental 
protection agency said thursday while lawmakers said the new 
policy could make some states into dumping grounds for radioactive 
garbage 
the decision last month by the nuclear regulatory commission to 
deregulate some lowlevel atomic wastes from laboratories 
hospitals and nuclear plants came under attack at a hearing by the 
house interior energy and environment subcommittee 
rep george miller dcalif the subcommittee chairman accused 
the nrc of coziness with the nuclear industry and said if the 
commission does not reverse its policy congress should protect 
states from being forced to accept such wastes in landfills 
at least two states including pennsylvania and maine already 
have enacted laws specifically prohibiting radioactive wastes in 
conventional landfills the nrc however has maintained that 
federal policy overrides state and local statutes 
under the policy announced june 27 lowlevel wastes including 
gloves clothing lab equipment dirt and even buildings and 
equipment at nuclear power plants can be disposed of as if they 
were normal garbage if radiation doses are below a certain level 
nrc chairman kenneth carr told the subcommittee that the issue 
is one of how safe is safe enough and promised that the 
public and the environment will remain properly protected 
but miller said the easing of federal requirements on such 
wastes has the potential to endanger the public health and is 
an open invitation to abuse by unscrupulous operators who want 
to dispose of radioactive materials 
some states that already are targets of outofstate garbage 
shipments fear they will become the dumping ground for 
radioactive wastes said rep joe rahall dwva he added if that 
becomes the case i fear there will be an allout rebellion in 
west virginia 
millers subcommittee released internal documents showing that 
both the epa and some nrc staff advisers have strongly opposed the 
nrc policy because they believe it covers too broad a range of 
lowlevel wastes the exemption from federal regulation would apply 
to wastes that subject individuals to radiation doses of less than 
10 millirems a year half the level of a normal chest xray 
we believe that is too high a level of exposure for a 
blanket deregulation criteria and is not protective of the public 
health the epas office of radiation programs concluded in a 
briefing paper made public by the subcommittee 
the epa estimated that the 10millirem threshold for regulatory 
action could result in as many as three additional cancer deaths 
for every 10000 people exposed 
richard guimond director of the office of radiation programs 
testified that one concern is the possible cumulative effect of the 
disposal of such wastes a single landfill for example may 
contain numerous categories of wastes each of which would be 
exempt because they individually meet the nrc cutoff for regulation 
the epa and some nrc staff members had urged that the cutoff be 
much lower guimond noted that the international atomic energy 
agency considered an individual dose of 1 millirem per year as a 
reasonable cutoff 
carr the nrc chairman said the agency would consider petitions 
for exemptions on a casebycase basis but he said a relaxation of 
controls on lowlevel wastes is needed to help return about 40 
nuclear sites under nrc jurisdiction to general use the energy 
department also has sought a clearer policy from the nrc on 
lowlevel wastes to help its cleanup of weapons plants 
no human endeavor involves a zero level of risk said carr 
the levels of radiation exposure we are talking about here while 
not zero are exceedingly small 
</TEXT>
