leaders of six indian tribes on thursday 
formally accepted an interior department agreement that gives them 
direct access to federal funds and more control over how to spend 
them 
the selfgovernance demonstration project is designed to test 
whether the tribes can do a better job of managing their own 
affairs than the federal government 
tribes from washington oklahoma california and minnesota were 
chosen to participate in the threeyear program which begins oct 
1 
under the program the tribes will get federal funds directly 
rather than through the bureau of indian affairs they will be free 
to spend the money as they choose 
the senate select committee on indian affairs reported last year 
that very little of the 33 billion allocated for indian programs 
actually reached indian people 
this is a major step for the six tribes represented here 
today interior secretary manuel lujan said as he gave the tribal 
leaders a copy of the agreement which was signed july 3 
through their individual agreements they are taking control 
of their budgets and they are setting priorities for future 
development in their unique cultural communities lujan said 
participating in the program are the quinault lummi and klallam 
tribes of washington the hoopa tribe of california the cherokee 
nation of oklahoma and the chippewas mille lacs band of minnesota 
lujan said that if the program is judged successful it will be 
extended to other tribes 
the chairman of the senate panel sen daniel inouye dhawaii 
said the new system will allow tribes to target particular needs in 
of health and education it also will give them a new sense of 
autonomy he said 
this ceremony here will bring in a new relationship a united 
statesindian partnership he said 
the 1991 amounts are quinault 39 million lummi 22 
million hoopa valley 2 million jamestown klallam 687000 
cherokee 61 million and mille lacs 267210 new annual funding 
agreements will be negotiated for 1992 and 1993 
