<TEXT>
the soviet union hardpressed for convertible 
currency with which to buy western goods and technology appears to 
be selling off some of its vast wealth of raw materials 
president mikhail s gorbachev said thursday his country does 
not intend to take aid free of charge but his prime minister 
has acknowledged the soviet union is in a most difficult 
hardcurrency situation 
the soviet ruble is not traded on world money markets making it 
difficult for the country to obtain western products that are much 
in demand at home where consumer goods are scarce and generally of 
poor quality 
recent kremlin decisions indicate the government is digging into 
its stores of raw materials for sale abroad or redirecting them for 
domestic use as well as getting ready to cut back on its foreign 
aid to allies 
although the west german government has guaranteed 31 billion 
in bank loans to moscow european community leaders refused to 
endorse an immediate 15 billion aid program at their houston 
meeting the leaders of the worlds seven largest capitalist 
countries this month refused to endorse a comprehensive aid program 
gorbachev said thursday after meeting with italian premier 
guilio andreotti that the soviet union is not seeking a handout 
from the west he told the communist party congress earlier this 
month that as far as such aid is concerned we act not as beggars 
but as partners and we are not going to take anything free of 
charge 
yet the soviet union clearly needs immediate cash infusions to 
avoid further economic decline 
we are at present in the most difficult hardcurrency 
situation soviet premier nikolai ryzhkov said in a speech last 
week as he outlined a new plan to rescue the economy 
on wednesday the soviets took a major step to get more hard 
currency de beers centenary ag signed an exclusive deal with 
moscow to sell the soviet unions rough diamond output 
de beers said it has agreed to make a secured advance of 1 
billion to the soviet union immediately against future diamond 
deliveries repayment would be made over five years beginning in 
november it said 
the soviet union has refused to deal directly with the south 
african company because of apartheid but now apparently has 
changed its mind 
foreign experts say the soviet union mines 10 million to 14 
million carats of diamonds a year and is the secondlargest 
producer after south africa 
in another move to soak up a domestic supply of hard currency 
the government on tuesday announced it was setting up a network of 
stores where soviet enterprises and organizations as well as 
individual citizens will be able to buy imported and highquality 
domestic goods for foreign currency 
it als said soviet citizens to spend their foreign cash in the 
soviet union beginning aug 1 without having to disclose where they 
got the money 
deputy prime minister stepan sitarian head of the governments 
economic commission said individual soviets had 200 million rubles 
324 million in foreign currency they had legally acquired but 
were unable to spend in the soviet union except at a few special 
shops for foreigners that have a limited amount of goods 
moscow also is changing its policies regarding raw materials for 
fellow socialist countries 
earlier this month ryzhkov announced that domestic needs 
especially for the upcoming harvest were forcing the soviet union 
the worlds largest oil producer to cut its oil exports by 
140000 barrels a day not only to western countries but to 
socialist bloc nations 
deliveries of bargainrate soviet oil supplies to cuba 
averaging about 90 million barrels annually already are being 
reduced 
a gorbachev decree made earlier this week warned developing 
countries presumably including cuba that the soviet union was 
reassessing its aid programs 
soviet aid to developing countries in 1989 was put at 12 billion 
rubles 19 billion or 14 percent of the gross national product 
according to the labor daily trud military aid is not included 
and western estimates are much higher 
v demchuk head of the socialist countries department of the 
state foreign economic committee of the council of ministers said 
in an interview published thursday in the government newspaper 
izvestia that the kremlin would be looking at getting a better 
return on its foreign investments 
a lot of money has been wasted on costly projects that had not 
been wellconsidered demchuk said 
he referred specifically to a plant in vietnam that was designed 
to produce 15000 diesel engines yet only built 500 soviet 
officials say that moscow gave vietnam about 10 billion rubles 
162 billion in credits for trade and technical asssistance from 
198690 
indicating vietnam cuba and mongolia demchuk said he thought 
it was reasonable to continue aid in building facilities to 
increase the export capabilities of each of those countries 
</TEXT>
