<TEXT>
russian president boris n yeltsin appealed 
thursday to farm workers to prevent a food shortage catastrophe 
in the largest soviet republic by harvesting this years crops as 
efficiently as possible 
yeltsins was the latest official bid to raise farm production 
in the soviet union food is rationed in many parts of the country 
and the nation every year must import us and canadian wheat 
as an incentive to agricultural workers yeltsin said the 
government would issue special harvest 90 coupons to 
agricultural workers from farmers to tractor drivers to food 
processors allowing them to buy consumer goods that have been in 
short supply 
details of the coupon program will be published in the coming 
days he said 
the existing food situation in our republic is critical 
yeltsin said in an appeal to the russian people published on the 
frontpage of the sovietskaya rossia newspaper to prevent a 
catastrophe we must improve it immediately 
in a separate interview russian prime minister ivan silayev 
said if the market is not soon saturated with food and consumer 
goods the situation will be unpredictable 
the prices will simply skyrocket he told pravitelstvenny 
vestnik newspaper 
yeltsin said a good harvest was expected in nearly all parts of 
the russian federation the most populous of the 15 soviet 
republics 
the us department of agriculture agrees forecasting this 
years soviet grain harvest will be 215 million tons slightly 
higher than last years 211 million tons 
we have to gather it carefully preserve it and get it onto 
the table of the russian people yeltsin said 
yeltsin acknowledged that farmers were tired of such pleas he 
agreed they needed more fuel workers and a better transportation 
network 
he said they should have more freedom to make independent 
decisions and to sell their surplus produce to whomever they want 
for whatever price they can negotiate 
yeltsin blamed the agricultural woes on the careless 
experiment started on our longsuffering land 
gorbachevs reforms are only beginning to change the communist 
collectivized system of land ownership and the governmentowned 
distribution system 
in his remarks yeltsin said the bonus coupons will be issued 
both for produce that is required to be sold to the state as well 
as for surplus produce sold for profit he said the government 
would create a fund of consumer goods that could be exchanged for 
the coupons but he did not say what goods would be included or 
where the government would get them 
organizations responsible for food storage and processing also 
will be eligible to encourage them to reduce harvest losses he 
said 
soviet president mikhail s gorbachev has said 25 percent of the 
countrys crops are lost during harvesting and storage 
gorbachev tried to raise national grain production and reduce 
imports last year by promising to pay farmers in foreign currency 
for exceeding their quotas newspapers said the program failed 
because most farmers didnt believe the offer was true and ignored 
it 
