<TEXT>
on a momentous day for the nations disabled 
president bush paid special tribute on thursday to a tacoma wash 
woman who was turned away from her hometown movie theater because 
of her wheelchair 
as he signed the americans with disabilities act bush said the 
new civil rights law will mean that theaters and other public 
accommodations including restaurants and shopping centers will no 
longer be able to shut out the handicapped 
these provisions mean so much to so many to one brave girl in 
particular they will mean the world bush said 
lisa carl a young washington state woman with cerebral palsy 
now will always be admitted to her hometown theater said the 
president 
lisa you might not have been welcome at your theater but 
ill tell you welcome to the white house were glad youre 
here he said to loud applause from the crowd of more than 3000 
including ms carl 
the 20yearold tacoma woman testified before a senate committee 
about the problems she has encountered including being turned away 
from a hometown theater 
she sued the bijou theater for not allowing her inside the 
theater contends that because of her disabilities the woman has 
special needs and should have been accompanied by an assistant the 
suit is still pending 
