<DOCNO> AP900726-0163 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a law that forbids state censorship of the media 
takes effect next week in the soviet union but the main censorship 
agency wont be abolished its director said in an interview 
published thursday 
chief soviet censor vladimir boldyrev said the glavlit 
censorship agency will continue to check foreign publications 
audio and visual materials mailed to the soviet union they will 
keep looking for calls to overthrow the government or criminal 
action pornography war propaganda violence and race or ethnic 
superiority 
we check books video and audio materials coming from abroad 
in line with international agreements and the international postal 
convention boldyrev told the government newspaper izvestia 
the press law debated for months before it was passed by the 
soviet legislature on june 12 takes effect aug 1 it states 
the press and other mass media are free and censorship of 
the mass media is forbidden 
it also gives any soviet citizen the right to establish a media 
outlet 
the law forbids publication of state secrets but the penalties 
are to be imposed on whoever leaked them rather than the journalist 
reporting them 
it also forbids slander and use of the mass media to interfere 
in citizens private lives infrigement on their honor and 
dignity pornography also remains outlawed 
boldyrev told izvestia that glavlit will offer the media three 
options for selfcensorship 
for the chief editor to assume all responsibility for what is 
published or broadcast 
for a specially appointed member of the editorial board to do 
it 
for the editor to enter into a contract with glavlit asking 
the agency to review and evaluate materials in this case glavlit 
would assume responsibility for not revealing state secrets 
glavlit the main administration for safeguarding state secrets 
in the press is the principal organ of censorship in the soviet 
union and an agency of the soviet council of ministers it is 
responsible for scrutinizing all official domestic publications 
from the press to dissertations as well those coming in from 
abroad by working with soviet customs and post office 
censorship and strict control of the media was a hallmark of 
soviet rule for decades a soviet journalists role was first to be 
a supporter of communist party policies and second to be a source 
of information the limited reports of the staterun media defined 
what millions of people knew about their country and the world 
although the new media law guarantees the right of soviets to 
found their own publications the countrys poor economy places 
practical restrictions on their newfound legal rights 
production of paper and printing plants still are part of the 
staterun economy which cannot produce enough newsprint 
scores of unofficial papers have appeared in the soviet union 
reflecting its new thirst for politics and debate their publishers 
must scramble to reach agreements with staterun printing houses to 
supply paper 
soviet president mikhail s gorbachev on july 15 decreed that 
communist party control of broadcasting outlets should end and 
competing voices be allowed to establish their own radio and 
television stations 
he hinted the supreme soviet would take up the matter with 
enabling legislation akin to the law that now allows private 
individuals to start publications 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

