heavy rain swamped parts of kansas iowa nebraska and minnesota 
on thursday causing flooding that closed roads and pushed rivers 
to their flood stage and beyond 
parts of the old highway west of salina kan were closed by 
flooding and the smoky hill river at elsworth was expected to 
crest about 6 feet higher than flood stage 
there was also flooding at tescott kan along a tributary to 
the saline river 
overnight rainfall up to 7 inches was reported across southwest 
iowa the heavy rain caused widespread flooding of rivers and 
streams 
up to 9 inches of rain since wednesday morning brought the 
nishnabotna river out of its banks the river crested more than 4 
feet higher than flood stage at randolph iowa on thursday morning 
the crest at hamburg iowa was 11 feet higher than flood stage 
but almost a foot less than the record flood of may 27 1987 
the heaviest rain reported in iowa was 9 inches at randolph 
between 7 am wednesday and 7 am thursday 
thunderstorms dumped up to 4 inches of rain thursday in 
southwestern minnesota and the twin cities area prompting flash 
flood warnings basement and road flooding was reported in redwood 
falls 
heavy thunderstorms dropped more than 5 inches of rain in parts 
of southeast nebraska bringing another round of flooding to a 
state pounded by severe weather and flooding in recent months 
early thursday afternoon rainshowers and thunderstorms were 
scattered from central arkansas into northern minnesota from 
southeastern south dakota across northeast kansas from southwest 
oklahoma across the texas big bend and along the central half of 
the texas gulf coast 
