<TEXT>
three weeks after a teacher was blamed for the 
accidental death of a 15yearold student japanese authorities on 
thursday decided to fire the teacher and discipline five other 
educators 
the case raised a storm of criticism about the strict rules that 
most schools in japan impose on their students and the rigorous 
enforcement that sometimes includes corporal punishment 
support for harsh disciplinary measures is widespread among 
teachers according to government polls parents and students 
generally do not complain about the rules or their enforcement 
until tragedies strike 
on july 6 teacher toshihiko hosoi 39 closed the front gate of 
a senior high school in kobe promptly at 830 am in line with 
school policy of starting classes on time 
ryoko ishida the student was caught in the heavy metal gate 
and died a few hours later of a crushed skull published accounts 
said 
on thursday the hyogo prefectural education board in western 
japan decided to fire hosoi for failing to take adequate safety 
measures police are questioning him 
the takatsuka senior high school principal atsuo nomura was 
given a warning and his resignation was accepted at the meeting of 
the education board 
the board also cautioned the schools head teacher and the local 
superintendent of education ryoji shimizu and reprimanded two 
vice superintendents of education 
commentator morse saito writing in mainichi shimbun newspaper 
said the schools strict gateclosing rule was designed to give 
students a way to earn recommendations for employment after 
graduation 
if students followed the ontime rule he wrote by 
graduation teachers could recommend most students as being 
prompt even though some had low grades this is important for 
students seeking employment after high school the elite dont 
need it 
other school rules require students to wear school uniforms even 
on sundays bar them from riding motorcycles or visiting bookstores 
or tea shops 
enforcing school rules includes keeping records of behavior 
such as promptness in files not accessible to students and 
parents files are passed on from junior high schools to high 
schools 
discipline also often includes corporal punishment according to 
morikatsu imahashi a professor at ibaraki university and a 
longtime critic of such methods 
teachers often slap punch kick he said in an interview 
justice ministry figures show that reports of corporal 
punishment more than doubled between 1984 and 1988 
extreme punishments can draw national attention last september 
teachers buried two junior high school students in fukuoka a city 
on the southern island of kyushu in sand up to their necks media 
reports said the teachers suspected the students of bullying their 
classmates the case caused a nationwide sensation when it came to 
light earlier this month 
with competition so intense for higher education students and 
parents arent inclined to protest out of fear it will be held 
against them those who imahashi said 
japans educational system is highly competitive and many 
students are being sent to cram schools called jukus to 
prepare for tests to get into good schools some children start 
intensive tutoring at ages as young as 3 in order to get into the 
best kindergartens and elementary schools especially those of 
respected private universities that automatically admit students 
from their own preparatory schools 
critics say some students who are under constant pressure to 
study rebel with truancy or acts of violence 
the number of pupils refusing to go to school has quadrupled to 
more than 42000 in the past 10 years according to a recent report 
by the prime ministers office 
police say reports of students attacking or murdering their 
mothers often in retaliation for enforcing study discipline are 
not uncommon 
the report by the prime ministers office placed much of the 
blame for juvenile problems on the educational system 
in their zeal for children to excel in exams that largely 
determine their future chances in life the strict school system 
and surrounding social environment have produced a generation of 
immature selfcentered unemotional youths the report said 
