<TEXT>
a us man paid 169000 on thursday for the 
ancient manorial title to a town in the heart of shakespearean 
england the manorial auctioneers said he gets the title a bit of 
pomp and ceremony and thats it 
joseph hardy of pittsburgh receives no land or property with his 
lordship of the manor of henleyinarden and he is not granted 
seat in the house of lords 
but he is entitled to preside over the annual ceremonial parade 
held each year in the town 80 miles northwest of london 
the document also confers the right to hold a weekly market and 
sit at the head of the long table at the annual dinner in the 
guildhall built in 1448 
the quaint village is nestled in the forest of arden seven 
miles northwest of stratforduponavon the birthplace of william 
shakespeare 
every year on the second tuesday in november a procession 
gathers at the 13thcentury market cross in henleyinarden the 
ceremonial court parade proceeds to the manorial church of st john 
the baptist and ends at the old guildhall for a dinner attended by 
local officials and other lords of the manor 
hardy accompanied at the london auction by his wife and three 
daughters is expected to take an active interest in preserving the 
traditions attached to his acquisition said robert smith chairman 
of the manorial society of great britain which helped arrange the 
auction 
other titles sold at auction thursday included the barony and 
manor of morpeth northumberland which brought 99500 and the 
barony lordship of frenchpark county roscommon ireland for 
54000 
lordships of the manor are the oldest titles in england 
predating the norman conquest of 1066 they once carried 
considerable land rights but their significance today is largely 
symbolic 
