<TEXT>
a panamanian lawsuit to be filed in 
miami accuses former strongman gen manuel antonio noriega of 
involvement in murder torture and drug trafficking according to 
legal papers obtained thursday the government is seeking up to 
65 billion in damages 
the 40page suit obtained from government sources by the 
associated press carries a laundry list of accusations with 11 
specific charges including fraud illicit enrichment racketeering 
and offenses against the panamanian people 
the suit asks that noriega and his allies repay panama at least 
500 million in damages it also asks for any damage award to be 
tripled which would make for a maximum of 15 billion 
in addition the suit seeks a separate 5 billion punitive 
payment 
panamanian officials have said they do not expect to recover 
that full amount but intend it as a statement of damage done to 
panama they said the suit will be filed within days 
the suit outlines cases of alleged assassination torture drug 
trafficking money laundering embezzlement illegal sale of visas 
and passports and abuse of authority while noriega headed the 
defunct panama defense forces 
from that position he controlled panamas government until he 
was ousted in december by the us invasion noriega was brought 
back to miami where he now faces us drugtrafficking charges 
the 1988 us indictment accuses noriega of taking 46 million 
in bribes from colombias medellin drug cartel to turn panama into 
a way station for cocaine trafficking 
panamas suit claims noriega earned about 700000 during his 28 
years as a military officer but is now worth an estimated 300 
million 
the governments lawyers john g kester gregory b craig and 
kevin j hasson contend in the suit that noriegas activities 
caused panama enormous material losses the suit says panama 
was damaged by a loss of tourism and an american trade embargo 
the suit names 19 codefendants they include marcos justines 
noriegas chief of staff who is jailed in panama city carlos 
duque the 1989 presidential candidate of noriegas party michael 
harari a former israeli military officer three former 
ambassadors noriegas wife felicidad and his mistress vicki amado 
however it was not clear if the panamanian government could 
recover money from those codefendants not in the united states 
the suit claims noriega was involved in the murder of army 
officers who plotted against him 
it also says noriega was paid 795 million for letting drugs 
flow through panama and 4 million to 7 million for protecting 
members of colombias medellin drug cartel 
it says that during the eight years noriega headed the armed 
forces he sold at least eight government planes for 7 million 
which he kept it did not name any buyer 
the suit also claims noriega diverted 12 million in government 
agricultural funds to his own use 
it claims government functionaries issued government checks for 
about 96 million to pay personal debts and that 12 million of 
that amount went to noriega 
it also accuses noriega of selling 2000 illegal passports at 
50000 each 
panamas attorney general rogelio cruz is to go to washington 
this week to further discuss the suit with the law firm of williams 
amp connolly 
