<TEXT>
a north korean broadcast said friday 
that five north korean citizens will cross the heavily fortified 
border into south korea during the day officials said 
on thursday communist north and capitalist south agreed to have 
their prime ministers meet in an unprecedented attempt to end 
hostility but within an hour of signing a row over the border 
crossing had the nations trading insults again 
the five were invited to seoul for a twoday meeting to plan a 
joint unification rally with south korean dissidents scheduled for 
aug 15 
it would be the first crossing by civilians with approval of 
both governments on the divided korean peninsula since a 1985 
family exchange 
south korean authorities quoted north korea as saying the five 
will pass over at panmunjom the truce village in the demilitarized 
zone and asking that they be met by the south korean dissidents 
south korea cautioned it will allow the border crossing only if 
north korea follows agreedupon rules to coordinate crossings 
between the two governments 
the five originally were expected to cross the border thursday 
they arrived at the frontier but a lastminute glitch developed 
over seouls housing arrangements south korea wanted the group to 
stay in a luxury hotel citing security reasons the north koreans 
wanted to stay with south korean dissidents at a church house and 
travel in the dissidents cars 
the outcome of that wrangle was not immediately disclosed 
namecalling protests and rhetoric over the accommodations 
issue threatened to cloud the premiers talks 
north and south korea were divided in 1945 at the end of world 
war ii despite years of hostility and a threeyear civil war in 
the early 1950s unification of their homeland remains a cherished 
dream by koreans on both sides of the border 
a political show said lee haehak one of three south 
korean dissident leaders who had gone to the truce village of 
panmunjom to welcome the north koreans 
down with president roh taewoo who blocks unification 
