<TEXT>
a honduran drug trafficker was found guilty 
thursday of racketeering kidnapping and conspiracy in the 1985 
abduction of us drug agent enrique camarena and his pilot who 
were killed in mexico 
the jury that convicted juan ramon matta ballesteros acquitted 
him of camarenas murder a crime that has strained relations 
between the united states and mexico 
mattas lawyer martin stolar said outside court the verdict 
was inconsistent and showed jury confusion 
stolar told reporters he believed extensive testimony about drug 
trafficking and corruption in the mexican government had distracted 
jurors from the main issue camarenas killing and had created 
the confusion 
he said he would appeal the convictions and asked us district 
judge edward rafeedie to overrule the jurys findings 
matta was one of four defendants charged in the camarena case 
but the jurors did not return verdicts against the others 
they didnt give a progress report on deliberations on the other 
three defendants and rafeedie told the they could return friday to 
resume their deliberations 
the 31yearold camarena was kidnapped off a street in 
guadalajara mexico in february 1985 tortured and interrogated by 
drug lords before being slain along with his mexican pilot alfredo 
zavala avelar 
after camarenas battered body was discovered a month later 
mexican authorities eventually pinned the blame on rafael caro 
quintero a swaggering 29yearold leader of the powerful 
guadalajara drug cartel 
camarenas colleagues were skeptical that the reckless 
illiterate rafa had acted alone the american authorities 
broadened their investigation to seek out the brains in the cartel 
including members of mexicos power elite and matta a wealthy 
honduran businessman also known as el negro 
prosecutors have said the cartel was incensed after camarenas 
undercover work led to the november 1984 seizure of 10000 tons of 
marijuana 
the trial was the second stemming from camarenas murder a 
crime which angry us authorities characterized as a reflection of 
official corruption in mexico 
judge rafeedie also presided over the first trial which 
resulted in the conviction of three men in 1988 
disputes between mexico and the united states over the case have 
erupted on several occasions throughout the investigation and 
trials 
earlier this month mexico said it would seek the extradition of 
a los angelesbased dea agent and a mexican informant who allegedly 
plotted the kidnapping of a guadalajara doctor accused in the 
killing 
matta a ealthy honduran businessman showed little reaction to 
the verdict except to shake his head slightly as if in disbelief 
mattas stature in his native honduras was such that his forced 
extradition in 1988 touched off street riots that left five people 
dead and torched the us embassy annex hondurans apparently were 
angered by the extradition and alarmed that mattas prosecution 
might harm the nations economy because he owned so many businesses 
tears streamed down the faces of his family who sat in the 
courtroom as the verdicts were announced 
earlier this year matta was convicted by another jury of 
operating a cocaine smuggling business 
matta was convicted in the ninth day of jury deliberations on 
charges of racketeering in the kidnapping and murder of camarena 
conspiring to kidnap camarena and the actual crime of kidnapping 
the agent and holding him for interrogation 
but jurors rejected the count that charged matta with actually 
murdering the us drug enforcement administration agent 
sentencing was set for sept 25 
earlier the jury had suggested in a note to the judge that some 
of the counts seemed to be convicting the defendant twice for the 
same crime a possible reason for the split verdict 
stolar insisted in his outofcourt statements that matta was 
tried illegally both in the camarena case and in the earlier drug 
trafficking case because he had been kidnapped from tegucigalpa by 
american authorities 
stolar had filed numerous challenges based on mattas arrest 
and all were rejected on appeal matta has been serving a life 
sentence on the drug conviction 
the dea has vowed to capture every person involved in the 
slaying so far 22 people have been charged in this country and 
more than 20 convicted in mexico among those held is rafael caro 
quintero alleged leader of the drug operation 
the other defendants in the current trial who were present 
during the reading of verdicts against matta were ruben zuno 
arce a guadalajara businessman who is the brotherinlaw of former 
mexican president luis echeverria juan jose bernabe ramirez a 
former mexican homicide officer and javier vasquez velasco a 
former bodyguard accused of murdering two american tourists in an 
apparent mistake killing 
