a few weeks ago when a car roared up and screeched to a halt 
some men jumped out and tried to shove me into the trunk he 
said i fought back and managed to get away when neighbors of my 
family started screaming 
hundreds of other slum youngsters suspected of taking drug money 
to kill policemen have been less fortunate 
more than 200 policemen in the medellin area have been killed 
this year in a war between the cocaine cartel and security forces 
no official figures are available on slain teenagers but the 
weekly news magazine la semana said in its july 16 edition that 
medellin death squads had killed about 1500 people in 1990 
mayor omar florez of medellin said there was little doubt some 
policemen and soldiers were violating human rights 
security forces who act outside the law are aggravating the 
state of violence and must be held accountable for their actions 
he said in an interview 
so far the central government in bogota has been unwilling or 
unable to stop the killings which occur almost daily 
people are snatched from the streets of slums and their bodies 
bound hand and foot often turn up in vacant lots or along highways 
the attorney generals office has concluded in the past that 
policemen were involved in death squads medellin police deny the 
accusations and say most of the killings result from gang rivalry 
emilio suarez a 62yearold resident of medellin said of the 
war between drug traffickers and police you in the united states 
see this as a battle of the good guys against the bad guys but we 
view it as the bad guys against the bad guys 
a woman who lives in the el playon slum spoke tearfully of her 
15yearold son now dead 
the law itself killed my boy he was just a regular 
hardworking high school student that boy was my last hope we are 
poor and i was counting on him for survival 
she and many others interviewed asked that their names not be 
used they were afraid of being killed by one side or the other 
death squad activity has diluted public confidence in the 
authorities the fact that officials have so little support from 
the people explains their failure in smashing the drug trade a 
human rights activist said 
he said the human rights organization he leads had scores of 
reports of murder disappearances and torture committed by 
policemen and soldiers 
people are blindfolded hanged by the neck beaten with sticks 
or forced to spend the night with bags over their heads while being 
questioned he said 
the army and police have become a symbol of death the 
activist declared they are carrying out a policy of 
extermination 
he asked not to be identified because his three predecessors 
were murdered 
mayor florez has invited victims of police abuse to speak out 
and press charges 
we are trying to reach the people to tell them they can come 
to us the mayors office for help but they are mostly keeping 
quiet because a climate of terror has been created here he said 
the mother of the murdered 15yearold said she was too 
frightened to step forward because i have been told that i too 
would be killed if i say anything 
president virgilio barco has been praised abroad for the 
crackdown on drug traffickers he began a year ago but domestic 
critics say his emergency measures opened the way to human rights 
violations 
cesar gaviria the president elect told reporters recently the 
government cannot fight the drug war with repression alone 
the countrys gravest problem now is violence in medellin and 
this will require special treatment from my government a treatment 
that transcends just military police and public order measures 
he said 
gaviria who takes office aug 7 pledged to support florezs 
100 million plan for rebuilding poor neighborhoods in this city of 
2 million people 
julio jaramillo a priest who recently published a study of 
medellin violence said the president and national security chiefs 
still had enough public support to bring offending policemen to 
justice 
many ranking officers have been replaced during an ambitious 
reorganization of the army and police begun in june 
florez said the shakeup would demonstrate that the governments 
intentions were good and will create an atmosphere which will 
allow people to trust authorities again 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

