<TEXT>
it is time for another generation to learn about 
edward r murrow a cbs newsman who died 25 years ago 
and there is no better way to begin than with edward r 
murrow this reporter airing monday nights on pbs series 
american masters for the next two weeks 
director susan steinberg and writer ed apfel wisely let murrows 
story tell itself with archival footage and interviews with his 
colleagues friends and family its narrated by the gorgeous 
beefsteak voice of charles kuralt 
this reporter is a definitive tv portrait of americas 
greatest broadcast journalist murrow personified the highest 
standards of his craft and ended his 22year career as its 
conscience and its prophet 
murrows broadcast career began in 1937 when he was a cbs news 
executive sent to europe to set up a network of correspondents to 
cover the gathering storm from the start he insisted on good 
reporters not professional announcers 
murrows boys who included eric sevareid howard k smith 
charles collingwood william shirer richard c hottelet and bill 
shadel reported world war ii from all fronts murrow though 
became the greatest of them 
this is london his deep resonant baritone reported 
from the embattled city at the height of the blitz electrifying 
the us radio audience in the days before this country entered 
world war ii 
after the war with the advent of television he and his 
colleagues learned the new medium virtually inventing the form of 
tv news documentary 
murrows high furrowed brow and everpresent cigarette he 
smoked three or four packs a day were trademarks of his weekly 
prime time news show see it now which began in 1951 
he took television to cover its first war korea in 1952 
in 1953 see it now reported the case of an air force 
officer who was discharged on the grounds that his father and 
sister were communist sympathizers public reactions forced the 
officers reinstatement 
it was the first time i think that ed and all of us 
understood the power of television said murrows longtime 
producer fred w friendly who went on to head cbs news 
murrows career peaked in march 1954 when see it now 
reported on sen joseph mccarthy rwis and his demagogic 
redbaiting investigation of alleged communist infiltration of the 
us government murrows wrapup 
the actions of the junior senator from wisconsin have caused 
alarm and dismay amongst our allies abroad and given considerable 
comfort to our enemies and whose fault is that not really his he 
didnt create this situation of fear he merely exploited it and 
rather successfully cassius was right the fault dear brutus is 
not in our stars but in ourselves 
then brow furrowed murrow ended with his trademark closing 
goodnight and good luck 
it was one of the greatest moments in television history it 
marked the beginning of the end for mccarthyism and it marked the 
beginning of murrows downfall 
he had become too powerful and cbs knew it over the next six 
years his declining health let the network erode his power and 
influence no journalist ever again will be as powerful 
in a 1958 speech murrow accused television of breaking its 
promise 
if this instrument is good for nothing but to entertain amuse 
and insulate then the tube is flickering now and we will soon see 
that the struggle is lost he said 
this instrument can teach it can illuminate yes and even it 
can inspire but it can do so only to the extent that humans are 
determined to use it to those ends otherwise its nothing but 
wires and lights in a box 
murrow died of lung cancer on april 27 1965 as eric sevareid 
said on that day he was a shooting star we will live in his 
afterglow a very long time 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
elsewhere in television 
further evidence that murrow was right words like 
shudderingly hideous stupid and awful just bubble 
right out of people whove seen room for romance a onehour 
anthology series starting on cbs tonight 
its brought to you by douglas s cramer whos partly to blame 
for love boat the publicity says the shows about the happy 
poignant romantic and humorous situations facing residents of an 
upscale apartment building 
right and love boat was an epic of the sea 
rebecca harrell plays an awful precocious wisecracking kid 
dom irrerra plays a sardonic concierge don novello best known as 
father guido sarducci was supposed to play him but must have seen 
the script 
room for romance takes dead aim on issues of the day 
unfortunately the day is sometime in the 70s and the issues are 
superstition breaking up and living with your fiancee its so 
stupid itll take points off your iq 
you have been warned 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

