<TEXT>
at the crack of dawn one 
wednesday 1500 soldiers swarmed into this seaside town and herded 
thousands of people onto the cricket field 
one by one the people were forced to pass through a tent men 
wearing hoods picked out those believed to be tamil guerrillas or 
their sympathizers and other soldiers searched homes 
by days end hundreds of men and women were taken away from 
trincomalee according to the government press reports and a 
western aid worker based in the town the operation was repeated 
over the next few days in each sector of this town of 48000 
people the government said 
since midjune government forces and separatist rebels have 
fought for control of the north and east ending a 13month truce 
in the 7yearold ethnic civil war 
few expect an early end to the war for a separate tamil homeland 
in sri lanka the island off indias tip that once was a paradise 
noted for tea spices beauty and peace 
many fear continued conflict will bring chaos more than 20000 
tamils have fled to india which has a tamil population of about 60 
million since the latest round of hostilities began 
fighting has reached a deadlock with the government controlling 
several main towns in the east but the guerrillas in charge of the 
north and the jungles 
maj gen gerry de silva the regional commander now says a 
political solution is the only way out a far cry from earlier army 
claims that it would quickly eliminate the liberation tigers of 
tamil eelam government commanders add however that negotiations 
are possible only from a position of strength 
a cycle of atrocities against civilians by both sides has 
resumed 
funerals of young children and mothers have become routine in 
trincomalee townspeople fly white flags on their bamboo fences as 
if they were surrendering to fate 
we are waiting to die said gloria williams whose small 
orphanage in a methodist church outside trincomalee was transformed 
into a refugee camp for 1000 old people and children all tamils 
all the teenagers have gone to the jungle to fight she 
said i pray to god but it doesnt help 
tamil rebels are believed to have massacred 600 unarmed 
policemen who surrendered when fighting resumed june 11 reports 
say they also killed hundreds of civilians most of them moslems 
whom the tigers accuse of helping the government 
according to other reports the government has executed many 
tamil civilians suspected of backing the militants masked police 
death squads led by members of tamil splinter groups working for 
the government comb major towns on the east coast picking out 
alleged supporters of the tigers 
the hooded ones came to my house last night ritah 
sivakamasundary a 36yearold tamil woman said in a refugee camp 
near trincomalee i heard gunshots after they took my husband 
away i dont know but i think hes dead 
western diplomats say the government has been the more 
restrained of the two sides there are no good guys in sri lanka 
but at least the government has made an effort to be disciplined 
one said on condition of anonymity 
he cited the rebels increasing use of pressure mines that blow 
off limbs a particularly inhumane type of weapon the mines 
nicknamed dice by sri lankan troops have maimed nearly 40 
soldiers 
sri lanka is one of asias most beautiful countries earlier 
this year while the ceasefire held the international monetary 
fund said its development prospects were among the regions 
brightest 
with a literacy rate of 90 percent relatively cheap labor 
liberal economic policies and abundant natural resources the 
island nation of 16 million people was touted as another singapore 
renewed hostilities will increase defense spending 50 percent 
this year to 170 million using up money neded for development a 
projected growth rate of 55 percent will not be achieved and 
international bankers say the country will be lucky to beat the 
1989 rate of 23 percent 
foreign investment which had been picking up after the united 
states helped establish a stock market is expected to lag the 
neglected southern half of the island could become even poorer 
raising the possibility of insurrection on two fronts 
a sinhalese nationalist movement centered in the south was 
crushed in 1989 
its terror campaign and the governments response cost 6000 
lives the tamil war has taken nearly 13000 
ethnic tensions between tamils who make up 18 percent of the 
population and sinhalese a predominant 75 percent go back 
hundreds of years 
in the teak and ivory drawing rooms of colombo the capital 
debate about which ethnic group arrived first harks back to 
centuries before christ 
in the modern era trouble began in 1956 eight years after sri 
lanka gained independence from britain 
tamils dominated sri lanka in colonial days the british gave 
them the best jobs and american missionaries set up the best 
schools in jaffna the tamil stronghold on the islands northern 
tip 
after independence the sinhalese majority voted its men into 
power in 1956 the government made sinhala the national language 
and buddhism the state religion 
this angered the tamils who have their own language and 
practice hinduism or christianity the day the law was passed 
riots broke out nationwide hundreds of people were killed 
the problem simmered boiled and simmered for 25 years sri 
lanka which entered the 1960s with a higher per capita income than 
south korea or malaysia fell behind in the economic race 
now the average citizen makes 367 a year near the bottom in 
asia 
ethnic tension turned into civil war in 1983 when 13 sinhalese 
soldiers were blown up by a land mine and sinhalese rioted in 
colombo killing scores of tamils 
tamil militants took to the jungles and fought until 1987 when 
india arranged a peace agreement and sent thousands of soldiers to 
disarm tamil guerrillas 
rebel groups agreed to the accord but the tigers reneged indian 
troops spent 32 months fighting the tigers then withdrew without 
success in march 1990 
western diplomats agree the tigers started the latest violence 
but say they do not understand why 
after the ceasefire in may 1989 the government gave the tigers 
wide autonomy in the north and east 
police were not allowed to make arrests unless the tigers 
approved the tigers levied taxes army troops were confined to 
barracks the tigers set up offices and roadblocks throughout the 
area and consolidated control 
one theory says the tigers jungle fighters for a decade could 
not adjust to the demands of a democratic political process 
in the past they had killed their enemies with peace they 
were forced to argue with them 
we had been thinking that we could evolve as a nation but 
this situation is terribly demoralizing said neelan tiruchelvam 
a moderate tamil leader we are back to square one 
</TEXT>
