the password is litmus 
thats the test nobody is supposed to give david h souter and 
it is likely to wind up as his shield against question a whether 
hed say yes or no on abortion rights 
to ask directly would be to apply the litmus test shunned by 
president bush and most democrats only the most ardent of abortion 
rights activists argue that a supreme court nominee can properly be 
required to say how he would rule on an issue certain to confront 
him on the bench 
so souter will be asked obliquely as a democratic senator put 
it 
litmus is the compound that turns red in acid solutions the 
test of the same name is one in which a single standard determines 
the outcome 
there was no single issue no litmus test or standard 
dominating my decision to nominate bush said campaigning in 
philadelphia a day after choosing souter a new hampshire jurist 
with a nearly blank slate on abortion cases and i will add 
there should be no litmus test in the process of confirmation 
the white house began issuing such injunctions even before bush 
chose his nominee to fend off the question of whether he would 
name anyone who did not agree with his view that the abortion 
rights decision of 1973 should be reversed 
souter himself was quoted by his friend sen warren b rudman 
rnh as saying he wouldnt have been interested in his 
appointment as a federal appeals judge earlier this year or in the 
supreme court if the administration had any litmus tests to apply 
rudman said nobody should ask a nominee how he would rule on 
specific cases that it would violate judicial ethics to answer 
such questions and make confirmation proceedings into a political 
popularity contest 
in that view of the way the senate should supreme court 
nominees the issues questions should be general about a nominees 
judicial philosophy view of the constitution and its guarantees 
not about specifics 
sen paul simon dill said souter wont be asked directly 
about things he might be ruling on from the bench but i think 
obliquely you do that he said by asking about his views on the 
right to privacy underpinning of the 1973 decision legalizing 
abortion 
that route to the a word has been used before 
robert h bork whose nomination was rejected by the senate in 
