<DOCNO> AP900726-0216 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
old mud dumped on the sea floor by giant 
underwater landslides provides new evidence that 13 devastating 
earthquakes may have rocked the pacific northwest during the last 
6900 years 
the study by john adams of the geological survey of canada also 
suggests there is a 2 percent to 10 percent chance that a quake 
measuring 8 or more on the richter scale will shake the region 
within the next 50 years 
several previous studies furnished evidence that at least six 
great earthquakes jolted the coasts of oregon and washington during 
the past several thousand years although no such quake has 
happened since pioneers settled the region 
adams study scheduled for publication in the august issue of 
the journal tectonics revealed a new line of evidence that the 
northwest is prone to giant earthquakes it also found geologic 
signs of 13 such quakes 
adams studied sea floor sediments called turbidites or layers 
of mud 
rivers carry mud and other debris into the ocean where it 
settles on the continental shelf and on the slope leading down to 
the deep sea floor the mud accumulates until the slope becomes too 
steep collapsing in a sudden undersea landslide called a turbidity 
current 
this current carries the mud into undersea channels or canyons 
where it settles to form turbidite deposits 
adams identified 13 layers of the turbidite muds in each of 
several undersea channels the remarkable discovery was that each 
layer was deposited simultaneously in all the channels that is 
for example the sixth layer in one channel was deposited at the 
same time as the sixth layer in the other channels 
that indicated each layer was created by a great earthquake 
which shook the sea floor so intensely it triggered huge undersea 
landslides up and down the oregonwashington coast he said 
it would have to be substantial to shake loose that much 
sediment adams said in a telephone interview from ottawa 
the 13 layers correspond to 13 great earthquakes which occurred 
an average of every 590 years give or take 170 years he said 
based on the frequency and evidence strongly indicating the most 
recent big jolt happened 300 years ago adams estimated the 
northwest is 2 percent to 10 percent likely to have another such 
quake within 50 years 
adams study was based on reanalysis of core samples of sea 
floor sediments collected from 1965 to 1968 by la verne kulm and 
other researchers at oregon state university 
he was able to date and correlate the turbidite layers in the 
various channels because they all were deposited after the eruption 
of the mount mazama volcano in oregons cascade range 6800 to 
6900 years ago the eruption is best known for creating the crater 
now named crater lake but it also spewed volcanic glass formed by 
the very rapid cooling of molten lava that was carried to sea and 
deposited on the ocean floor 
adams study adds to other evidence that the northwest has been 
rocked by powerful quakes said brian atwater a us geological 
survey geophysicist who uncovered some of the first evidence for 
such prehistoric seismic disasters 
but atwater and kulm said another possible explanation for 
adams findings is that sediment perched on the continental shelf 
merely breaks loose at regular intervals after big storms or when 
enough has accumulated to trigger an undersea landslide 
you can get that kind of regularity by loading sediment on the 
ocean shelf kulm said noting that turbidity currents happen 
every 10 to 25 years near the mouth of the mississippi river in the 
gulf of mexico 
but he said sediments accumulate more rapidly there than off the 
northwest coast and that 400 to 600year intervals between 
turbidity currents is a pretty long time if the landslides were 
triggered by slope collapse rather than big earthquakes 
so earthquakes are most certainly a strong possibility to 
explain the turbidites off oregon and washington kulm said 
atwater said that early this century the great grand banks 
earthquake off newfoundlands coast sent debris crashing down the 
undersea channels of the atlantic to snap telephone cables 
adams said it is possible that simple sediment accumulation or 
even major storms could have triggered the turbidity currents but 
the range and frequency indicate the most likely cause is a major 
earthquake he said 
atwater unearthed some of the first evidence of prehistoric 
great quakes in the northwest several years ago he found that 
estuaries such as washingtons willapa bay and oregons netarts bay 
contained alternating layers of peat covered by sand that 
indicated repeated instances in which the coastline dropped 
vertically in a great quake then was inundated by tsunamis or 
giant sea waves that dumped sand on coastal marshes 
david yamaguchi a university of colorado scientist has found 
evidence in tree rings that trees along 60 miles of the washington 
coast died suddenly 300 years ago when they were submerged by a 
tsunami 
adams study certainly complements the estuary evidence and 
the tree ring studies atwater said 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP900726-0217 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
on a barren windswept plain kerry 
sieh digs trenches across the san andreas fault trying to unravel 
the secrets of prehistoric earthquakes so he can forecast disasters 
here in the shadow of the temblor range 130 miles northwest of 
los angeles sieh spends hundreds of hours 15 feet underground 
using a tape measure finepoint pencil and laptop drawing board 
he makes detailed maps of beds of sediment in the walls of his 
trenches 
i expose layers that go back hundreds or thousands of years 
and i see where the san andreas fault has broken those sediments 
said sieh a 39yearold geologist at the california institute of 
technology 
by dating those sediments with radiocarbon methods i can tell 
when prehistoric earthquakes occurred that helps me understand 
what is likely to happen in the future 
over the past 15 years siehs meticulous research helped alert 
millions of southern californians to a horrible secret once hidden 
in the earth 
within the next few decades there is at least a 60 percent 
chance that the region will be rocked by the big one a disastrous 
quake measuring 75 to 8 or more on the richter scale 
scientists know the last such disaster the fort tejon 
earthquake shook a sparsely populated southern california in 
1857 decades before a similar jolt at the northern end of the san 
andreas ravaged san francisco in 1906 
before siehs pioneering studies of the southern san andreas no 
one knew how often great earthquakes shook southern california so 
people had no idea when another such quake might be expected 
his work certainly has had a major impact on our view of the 
probability of major earthquakes in southern california said 
robert wallace retired chief scientist of the us geological 
surveys office of earthquake studies his work drove the policy 
of the los angeles area toward real serious planning for a major 
earthquake 
los angeles city councilman hal bernson credited siehs findings 
for triggering many of the measures weve undertaken as far as 
public preparedness is concerned he cited a 1981 ordinance 
requiring reinforcement or demolition of thousands of vulnerable 
brick buildings 
california is quakeprone because it straddles two great plates 
that make up earths crust quakes happen as the pacific plate 
grinds slowly northwest past the north american plate along the 
700milelong san andreas and a network of related faults 
the entire fault doesnt snap at once because of changes in 
rock type or bends in the fault separate segments of the san 
andreas break alone or in combination to cause quakes 
three segments that extend 200 miles ruptured to cause the 1857 
fort tejon earthquake from northwest to southeast they were the 
cholame segment in central california the carrizo plain segment 
and the mojave segment which extends from tejon pass north of los 
angeles to cajon pass north of san bernardino 
as a geology student at the university of california riverside 
in the early 1970s sieh theorized that by digging trenches across 
various segments of the fault he could determine how often great 
quakes had ruptured each section the method known as 
paleoseismology let him estimate how soon big jolts might happen 
again 
he showed seismologists they could learn something from 
geologists who study rocks and sediments instead of seismographic 
records of recent quakes 
the whole idea that we can talk about probabilities of future 
earthquakes happened because of kerrys work said lucile jones 
a seismologist with the us geological survey his work is so 
fundamental it has changed the field 
in the mid1970s siehs work indicated there was a 50 percent 
to 90 percent chance a great quake would shake southern california 
within 50 years later research by sieh and others prompted a 
formal forecast in 1988 by the geological survey which said there 
was at least a 60 percent chance of such a disaster within 30 years 
siehs early research indicated the next big one would rupture 
the faults mojave segment the segment closest to los angeles a 
1980 federal report estimated such a quake could kill up to 14000 
people hospitalize 55000 and cause 17 billion in damage 
but siehs more recent findings suggest the big one is most 
likely to rupture the san andreas faults coachella valley segment 
between the palm springs area and the salton sea 
because such a quake would be more distant from los angeles 
damage likely would be less than envisioned in the 1980 estimate 
unless the fault continued to rupture northward breaking both the 
coachella valley and mojave segments 
on the carrizo plain the most recent findings by sieh and usgs 
scientist carol prentice indicate that segment of the fault is 
unlikely to break soon in an exact repeat of the great quake of 
1857 
while siehs continuing studies changed details about the likely 
location of southern californias next big one his work provided 
hardandfast proof it is inevitable author john nance wrote 
in the 1988 book on shaky ground 
no longer could residents or government officials of southern 
california treat the prospect of great earthquakes on the southern 
san andreas as the mere armchair postulations of theorizing 
scientists nance said 
sieh said that when he digs into the mighty san andreas he 
doesnt think about the catastrophes it ultimately will unleash 
i do what i do because its fun he said but i enjoy 
doing something that helps other people 
so often what people do in response to earthquake hazards is 
stick their heads in the sand we need to do whatever we can to 
reduce the property losses and to reduce losses of life if i can 
say roughly when and where earthquakes are going to happen id 
hope people would be responsible and rational enough to deal with 
it 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

