<TEXT>
editors note the governments research and development 
programs a 64 billion source of technological breakthroughs and 
national pride are also a vulnerable target for budgetcutters 
this is the third in an occasional series examining one portion of 
this years federal budget science spending 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the two companies competing to build 1 
billion worth of bussized magnets for the superconducting super 
collider both have promised to manufacture them in the home state 
of a key senator 
the national science foundation a government agency hoping to 
expand its budget treated five congressional staffers to a tour of 
us research stations in antarctica and the private national 
foundation for ileitis and colitis got the actress mary ann mobley 
to beseech a congressional committee to boost spending on the 
digestive diseases 
its all part of the increasingly intense competition for 
federal research and development dollars though the kitty will 
reach 64 billion this year of a 12 trillion overall budget 
scientists say it is too small 
federal science spending is feeling pressure from within and 
without the huge federal deficit means there is less money for all 
government programs including science 
there also are demands on the governments science dollar from a 
growing number of bigticket projects like the 8 billion super 
collider an atom smasher to be built in texas and the 30 billion 
space station thus researchers are vying ever harder to persuade 
congress to give them a piece of the budget pie 
there is a lot of money out there but these sums are 
considerably less than is needed to do the job and the competition 
is greater said jerold roschwalb lobbyist for the national 
association of state universities and land grant colleges whose 
schools rely heavily on federal research aid 
the situation has driven some scientists to venture into 
congress budget process as never before 
recently two groups the american society for cell biology and 
the american society for biochemistry and molecular biology hired 
former maine democratic rep peter kyros for about 100000 to 
lobby congress to increase federal medical research grants 
our members felt the situation had gotten so bad that it was 
time for something new and innovative said peter farnham 
spokesman for the biochemistry society all of our members live 
and die on the availability of these grants 
other scientific organizations have long believed that getting 
active in the budget process is a must about 20 colleges and 
universities have lobbying offices in washington while dozens of 
others have retained lobbying firms 
john farrar president of the digestive disease national 
coalition testified before the house and senate appropriations 
committees for five years before showing up this year with mobley 
an actress who has battled her own digestive ailments 
the fact is nobody knows what his appearances accomplish 
farrar said but it seems to me if you dont show up you know 
you wont get your share 
dangling jobs is another approach 
last summer general dynamics announced that if the department 
of energy picked it to build giant magnets for the super collider 
it would manufacture them in hammond la 
its competitor grumman corp said in may of this year that it 
would build the magnets in shreveport la if it won the 
competition 
