<TEXT>
the last of the big brick textile mills 
that once dominated this little town in the berkshires is scheduled 
to close next spring putting nearly 400 people out of work 
this is a tremendous loss said mark pasquini executive 
director of the northern berkshire industrial park and development 
after company officials announced they were closing the waverly 
fabrics mill and shifting its operations to south carolina and 
delaware 
last fall officials of new yorkbased f schumacher amp co 
which owns waverly announced they planned to cut back the adams 
operation to a regional distribution and custom sewing center 
employing about 230 workers 
but on tuesday james hinthorn vice president of human 
resources for f schumacher announced the entire adams operation 
would be phased out by april 1991 except for a retail outlet store 
our concept of a regional distribution center and regional 
customer workroom was predicated on sales continuing to grow 
rapidly he said unfortunately sales in the northeast are 
substantially below what we had anticipated and that made it very 
difficult from a business standpoint to justify continuing 
operations 
for decades waverly has been known for fine fabrics for home 
furnishings the adams plant produces draperies bed covers 
curtains and pillows 
its future in this community of 9000 people has been uncertain 
since the arnold print works a dyeing plant that had been one of 
its main suppliers shut down in 1984 despite state efforts to 
save it the two plants had together employed more than 1000 
people 
the sprawling waverly plant was once part of the massive 
fourmill berkshire cotton manufacturing co complex that employed 
3000 people at the turn of the century in 1910 when the mills 
were booming they swelled the population of the town to 13106 
people a figure never since equalled 
but in the 1930s the company was sold to berkshire hathaway and 
by the 1950s the last of its operations here had left for the south 
waverly and the state department of employment and training set 
up a workers assistance center last month to help workers cope with 
the layoffs the company announced last fall 
well have to find new jobs we have no choice but where 
said norma sebastino she has worked at the plant for 18 years and 
her husband for 28 years 
my husband is 61 where is he going to start im 53 where am 
i going to start she said weve got a home weve got 
children 
