<DOCNO> AP900726-0226 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
federal regulators approved a rule that will 
allow a circuit breaker to limit index arbitrage on the new 
york stock exchange when the dow jones industrial average rises or 
falls 50 points 
the change was approved unanimously by the securities and 
exchange commission although all four commissioners expressed 
misgivings about the 50point threshhold 
the change is a oneyear pilot program with the big board 
required to give the sec a progress report after six months 
the proposal actually an amendment to an existing nyse rule 
would limit index arbitrage to selling at or above the previous 
lowest price when the dow jones average is down 50 points i would 
also limit buying at or below the previous highest price when the 
average is above 50 points 
index arbitrage is a computerized trading strategy through which 
traders try to take advantage of small price differences between 
the stock and futures markets by simultaneously buying large orders 
in one market while selling in the other 
critics have blamed program trading particularly index 
arbitrage for worsening market drops like the 1987 stock market 
crash the 190point drop last oct 13 and mondays 100point fall 
mondays drop triggered circuit breakers which prompted 
brief trading halts on futures markets at the chicago board of 
trade and the chicago mercantile exchange 
the nyse first proposed an index arbitrage circuit breaker last 
february 
in a written statement issued after the sec vote the big board 
said the rule change would minimize excess market volatility that 
might be due to index arbitrage the move should promote market 
stabilization and enhance investor confidence the exchange said 
under the rule change when the dow jones average goes below 50 
points or more from the previous days close index arbitrage 
orders to sell any stock listed in the sampp 500 stock price index 
can only be executed when the price is at or above the previous 
lowest price 
conversely when the dow rises 50 or more points buy orders can 
only be executed when the price is at or below the previous highest 
price 
sec chairman richard c breeden said he was voting for the rule 
change although i am unhappy with some of the aspects of this 
breeden said hes rather cure the disease instead of just 
treating it for him the disease is the low level of margins in 
the futures markets margins are the downpayments or collateral 
paid by investors who buy securities or futures contracts on 
credit currently futures margins are set by the exchanges 
usually only a fraction of the amount required in securities 
transactions 
breeden has been lobbying congress to have authority for stock 
index futures and their margins transferred to the sec 
i have substantial doubts whether 50 points is the right 
trigger said commissioner phil lochner 
the staff has that concern as does obviously a number of 
commissioners richard ketchum head of the secs division of 
market regulation after the vote fifty points triggers a 
reasonable number of times in a year and there is a worry about 
any artificial impediments to trading at that level 
on the other hand trading on monday was a pretty good 
indication that where the stock prices really picked up speed 
where the slope of the decline increased was around 50 points and 
where the futures price diverged from the stock price also was 
around 50 points added ketchum who called 50 points a 
reasonable indicator 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

