<TEXT>
government subsidies that assure farmers 
certain income and the nation a predictable food supply are holding 
fast as congress moves toward completion of the 1990 farm bill 
after vigorous debate the house on wednesday defeated 263169 
a proposal by reps richard armey rtexas and charles schumer 
dny to strip subsidies from farmers with adjusted gross incomes 
of 100000 or more it would have affected about 20000 farm 
operations 
members of the agriculture committee persuaded colleagues to 
stick with the panels intention to support huge and small farmers 
alike as a means of controlling the food supply 
the house planned to complete debate and pass its version of the 
approximately 55 billion fiveyear bill on friday the senate was 
resuming debate today 
i honestly was surprised agriculture committee chairman 
kika de la garza dtexas said of the vote on the armeyschumer 
amendment i was feeling a much closer vote 
he said environmental and labor organizations were helping his 
side 
if you drive farmers out of the program you take acres out of 
the program that you will not be able to keep environmentally 
sound de la garza said 
as for organized labor he said i think their interest is 
jobs like i tell my friends in the uaw united auto workers in 
detroit no farmer no pickup 
armey said he and his supporters knew they were underdogs before 
the vote we wanted to shape the debate with the interests of 
consumers taxpayers and small farmers in mind and we were 
successful in that regard he said 
urban lawmakers said they did not understand why the wealthiest 
farmers could not be cut free when aid to the poor was consistently 
being reduced 
armey said the amendment would have saved 900 million annually 
from the approximately 10 billion a year the bill foresees 
spending to support wheat corn cotton soybeans and rice 
these people are not the family farmer said schumer their 
income from the farm is only 4 percent of their income 
yes they are the large agricultural businesses that dont 
need subsidies the investors and the multimillionaires who 
farm for a hobby they are investors who live far away and 
dont even till the soil 
rep edward madigan of illinois the ranking republican on the 
agriculture committee argued that the schumerarmey amendment 
would cost the taxpayers more than the program in the bill 
it would take farmers out of control of the government enabling 
them to put more land into production and cause surpluses that 
would drive prices down madigan said farmers still in the program 
would get high deficiency payments from the government if prices 
went too low he said 
besides establishing price support programs for commodities the 
farm bill sets policy for nutrition programs agricultural exports 
soil and water conservation agricultural research and extension 
work food inspection and other responsibilities of the agriculture 
department 
in other action wednesday both the house and senate fended off 
attacks on the peanut program one of the most protectionist 
programs in agriculture 
a senate amendment that would have ended quotas removed all 
restrictions on the planting of peanuts and authorized the 
secretary of agriculture to establish a new price support for the 
crop was defeated 5741 
the house ruled an identical amendment out of order after rep 
charles hatcher dga cited a congressional budget office 
estimate that the amendment would cost the taxpayers 55 million 
next year 
the house also 
accepted an amendment 256164 that would require the 
agriculture secretary to start a management program for dairy 
products if surpluses reached 6 billion pounds instead of the 7 
billion pounds originally in the bill 
approved an amendment on voice vote to gradually lower supports 
on wool and mohair from 200000 per producer in 1991 to 100000 
in 1994 
the senate meanwhile rejected 7226 an effort to tie target 
prices to the consumer price index minus 43 percent 
