<TEXT>
general electric co reached an agreement 
with the government today to pay a 10 million criminal fine for 
defrauding the army on an 8 million battlefield computer system 
the punishment stemming from ges conviction in a case earlier 
this year is one of the largest levied against a company in a 
defense fraud but far less than the government initially wanted 
which could have exceeded 50 million 
the agreement also called for the nations fifthlargest 
industrial company to pay 83 million to settle related civil 
suits and 117 million settle unrelated matters with the 
government that hadnt reached the litigation stage 
us district judge lowell reed jr who accepted the agreement 
and sentenced two former company employees involved in the case 
called the criminal fine against the company adequate fair and 
in the best interest of the public 
ge said in a statement that company executives felt it was 
time to close these old cases which date back to the early 1980s 
and were pleased that the government has recognized the 
significance and the value of the improved procedures that ge 
started in 1985 by recommending a fine that is far less than the 
amount they originally sought 
the judge said he had concluded the fine against ge was 
appropriate as he accepted the agreement which also says ge 
relinquishes rights to appeal 
the fine put ge into the ranks of large companies that have paid 
multimillion dollar fines for cheating the government on defense 
work in recent years 
northrop corp agreed to pay a 17 million fine in february for 
falsifying records on parts for the cruise missile and harrier jet 
in 1988 sundstrand corp agreed to pay a record fine of 115 
million the largest fraud settlement in pentagon history 
former ge employee gerald a leo 52 who was convicted of four 
counts of mail fraud and one count of trying to deceive federal 
investigators was sentenced to 10 months in prison and fined 
15000 
he never did anything yelled his sobbing wife mary when 
the sentence was imposed 
codefendant james badolato 43 convicted of misleading 
auditors and smbmitting false documents was to be sentenced later 
both had worked for a ge subsidiary management amp technical 
services co 
the company and the two employees were convicted this february 
on a case stemming from a 1983 investigation 
the government charged that the ge subsidiary did not tell the 
government in 1983 that it had found substantially less expensive 
subcontractors to help build the battlefield computer system part 
of a 250 million defense contract 
