<TEXT>
opec oil ministers said thursday they agreed to 
raise the cartels ceiling price for crude oil and opec president 
sadek boussena criticized members who drove down the price by 
exceeding production quotas 
his comments were apparently directed in part at kuwait and the 
united arab emirates who are blamed for keeping oil prices low by 
cheating on their quotas 
opecs decision to raise the ceiling price came after it 
received assurances that overproduction by kuwait and the uae 
would end and that overall world production of oil would decrease 
the price of wholesale unleaded gasoline rose 22 cents a gallon 
thursday on the new york mercantile exchange settling at 6526 
cents partly in anticipation that opec members may soon reach a 
formal agreement for cutting oil production 
the market perception is that opec is serious this time 
william byers an energy analyst with bear stearns amp co said 
if opec can reach an accord and make it stick its going to mean 
higher prices for consumers at the pumps 
a row between kuwait and iraq over the quota issue appeared to 
have been defused as the ministers of the 13nation group began 
their regular midyear conference 
iraqi oil minister issam abdul raheem alchalabi sat next to his 
kuwaiti counterpart rashid saleem alameeri at the conference 
table the two chatted and laughed before the start of the meeting 
iraq on thursday scaled back a weeklong intimidation campaign 
against kuwait which reportedly included a military buildup along 
the iraqkuwait border leaders of kuwait and iraq were scheduled 
to meet in saudi arabia this weekend to try to resolve their 
differences 
a ministerial source said formal agreement was near on raising 
opecs target price several dollars a barrel and setting a new 
production ceiling of 225 million barrels a day for the entire 
cartel this would be an increase over the current ceiling of 2209 
million but far short of the 235 million barrels that experts say 
the cartel has actually been producing 
the new benchmark price is expected to be 21 to 22 per barrel 
the source said iraq had hoped for 25 a barrel 
the current 18 target price was set in december 1986 but an 
oil glut sent prices down to as low as 1364 a barrel this year 
the price rose to 1625 a barrel last week 
every dollar decline or rise in the price of a barrel of oil 
amounts to about a fivecent change in gas prices for consumers at 
the pump 
the source predicted the ministers of the organization of 
petroleum exporting countries would ratify the accord friday when 
formal talks resumed 
algerian oil minister boussena opecs new president told 
reporters after a twohour midday session we will have a new 
minimum reference price 
there are several positions but all of them are accepting 
higher prices he said 
indonesian minister ginandjar kartasasmita elected opecs 
alternate president said there is a general feeling that we 
want to have the price at least 20 
libyan minister fawzi shakshuki demanded a higher production 
quota for his country before agreeing to a new cartel production 
cap of 225 million barrels a day as proposed by saudi arabia and 
other persian gulf producers 
under the proposal only the uae production quota would 
increase by 400000 barrels a day all other quotas would remain 
the same 
shakshuki said there should be no increase unless libya 
shares 
the ministers of kuwait and the united arab emirates denied 
their countries have been producing more than their quotas 15 
million barrels for kuwait and 11 million for the uae analysts 
say each has been pumping about 2 million barrels daily 
the alleged overproduction was at the heart of the recent rise 
in tensions involving iraq iraq badly in need of cash to rebuild 
after eight years of war with iran claims it has lost 14 billion 
in oil revenues because of low prices caused by overproduction 
iraqi president saddam hussein last week threatened to retaliate 
against countries ignoring their opec production caps he also 
accused kuwait of stealing 24 billion worth of oil from a field 
that includes land claimed by both countries 
boussena denounced violations of output caps 
opecs fortunes have faded badly and the nations economies 
risk being brought to the brink of collapse he said 
