<TEXT>
a drop in crude oil prices worked to depress earnings at texaco 
inc and phillips petroleum co during the second quarter but 
mobil corp and chevron corp managed to improve results during the 
period the companies reported tuesday 
though relatively strong during the years first quarter crude 
oil prices fell an average of 4 a barrel in the subsequent quarter 
because of worldwide oversupply as a result texacos profits 
during the period slipped 4 percent while phillips reported a 47 
percent tumble in net income 
several other major oil companies have reported lower earnings 
due to lower crude prices including atlantic richfield co amoco 
and amerada hess corp 
but mobil the nations secondlargest oil concern reported a 
24 percent jump in net income largely due to special factors and 
profits at chevron were up a sharp 60 percent 
pennzoil co reported a 96 percent drop in profits blaming the 
sale of shortterm securities and purchase of chevron common stock 
and restructuring charges in the second quarter of 1990 the 
company also said a onetime gain recorded in last years second 
quarter contributed to the steep drop 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
mobil estimated net income for the second quarter at 498 
million or 119 a share up from 401 million or 98 cents a 
share a year earlier the 1990 quarter got a 182 million boost 
from the sale of a 5 percent stake in a north sea oil field and the 
sale of mobils refining and fuels marketing business in italy 
revenue for the period was 138 billion off 1 percent from 14 
billion in the yearago period 
mobil chairman allen e murray said excluding special items 
petroleum operations were slightly lower than a year earlier and 
stronger refining margins did not offset sharply lower crude oil 
prices the companys chemical operations also reported lower 
results 
for the first half mobil estimated net earnings at 898 
million or 213 a share up 8 percent from 830 million or 202 
a share in the first half of 1989 excluding special items 
firsthalf earnings of 856 million were down 114 million from the 
yearago level 
revenue for the period increased 3 percent to 289 billion 
from 281 billion in the first half of 1989 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
texaco the nations thirdlargest oil company said net income 
during the quarter totaled 353 million or 126 a share down 
from 366 million or 139 a share a year ago 
revenue rose 3 percent to 872 billion from 845 billion a 
year ago largely because of higher crude and oil product sales 
volumes 
in addition to lower crude prices during the second quarter 
natural gas prices also fell and petrochemical results were 
significantly lower because of oversupply and reduced 
demand texaco chief executive and president james w kinnear 
said in a statement from the companys white plains ny 
headquarters 
for the years first half texaco reported net income of 681 
million or 241 a share down 63 percent from 182 billion or 
719 a share in the yearago period which included a 119 
billion gain from the sale of texaco canada inc without the gain 
net income was up 8 percent the company said 
firsthalf revenue was off 1 percent at 1788 billion from 
1806 billion 
</TEXT>
